{"title_page": "Hugh Hewitt", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{infobox person\n| name               = Hugh Hewitt\n| image              = Hugh Hewitt by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption            = Hewitt speaking in January 2017\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1956|2|22}}\n| birth_place        = [[Warren, Ohio]], U.S.\n| television         = ''Hugh Hewitt''\n| alma_mater         = [[Harvard University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[University of Michigan]] {{small|([[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n| party              = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| residence          = [[Orange, California]], U.S.\n| home_town           = [[Warren, Ohio]], U.S.\n| occupation         = Radio talk show host, lawyer, law professor, [[Television presenter|Television host]], political commentator, author\n| employer           = [[Salem Radio Network]]<br>[[NBC News]]/[[MSNBC]]<br>[[Chapman University School of Law]]<br>[[Richard Nixon Foundation]]\n| years_active       = 1983\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Betsy Hewitt|1982}}\n}}\n\n'''Hugh Hewitt''' (born February 22, 1956) is an American radio talk show host with the [[Salem Radio Network]] and an attorney, [[academic]], and author. Generally a [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]], he writes about law, society, politics, and [[media bias in the United States]]. Hewitt is president and CEO of the [[Richard Nixon Foundation]], a law professor at [[Chapman University School of Law]], a columnist for the ''[[Washington Post]]'', and a regular political commentator on [[NBC News]] and [[MSNBC]].\n\n== Early life ==\nHewitt is the son of Marguerite (n\u00e9e Rohl) and William Robert Hewitt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ieYTAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA137 |title=The Happiest Life|work=google.ca|accessdate=February 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tributes.com/show/Atty.-William-R.-Hewitt-88199041|title=Atty. Hewitt  Obituary  \u2013 Ohio \u2013 Tributes.com|work=tributes.com|accessdate=February 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://records.ancestry.com/hugh_z_hewitt_records.ashx?pid=129399466|title=Hugh Z Hewitt|work=ancestry.com|accessdate=February 24, 2015}}</ref> He describes himself as \"a descendant of both [[Ulster]] and [[Republic of Ireland|the Republic]] through a green-orange marriage of immigrants from [[County Down]] and [[County Clare]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2019/12/07/free-world-needs-boris-johnson/|title=Opinion &#124; The free world needs Boris Johnson|first=Hugh Hewitt closeHugh|last=HewittBioBioFollowFollow|website=Washington Post}}</ref> He attended [[John F. Kennedy High School (Warren, Ohio)|John F. Kennedy Catholic High School]]<ref>[http://www.warrenjfk.com/?page=alumgolden Golden Eagle Alumni Award] John F. Kennedy Catholic School</ref> in [[Warren, Ohio]], and [[Harvard College|Harvard University]], and graduated ''[[cum laude]]'' with a [[Bachelors of Arts|B.A.]] in government in 1978. After leaving Harvard, he worked as a ghostwriter for [[Richard Nixon]] in [[California]] and [[New York (state)|New York]], before studying at the [[University of Michigan Law School]], where he was inducted into the [[Order of the Coif]]. Hewitt received his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree in 1983, then moved to [[Washington D.C.]] to clerk for Judges [[Roger Robb]] and [[George MacKinnon]] on the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit]] in 1983\u201384.\n\nHewitt worked in many posts in the [[Ronald Reagan|Reagan]] administration, including Deputy Director and General Counsel of the [[United States Office of Personnel Management|Office of Personnel Management]], General Counsel for the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]], Assistant [[White House Counsel]] and Special Assistant to the [[United States Attorney General|Attorney General]].<ref>[http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=35466 Nomination of Hugh Hewitt To Be Deputy Director of the Office of Personnel Management] The American Presidency Project.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHewitt returned to California in 1989 to oversee construction of the [[Richard Nixon Presidential Library and Museum]] as the library's executive director from groundbreaking through dedication and opening.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/socal/daily-pilot/entertainment/tn-wknd-et-nixon-20190328-story.html|title=Conservative commentator Hugh Hewitt to become president of the Richard Nixon Foundation|date=2019-03-27|website=Daily Pilot|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> In 1990, Hewitt sparked controversy by proposing screening of researchers wishing to use the library resources. Hewitt suggested refusing admission to researchers deemed \"unfriendly\" \u2013 specifically [[Bob Woodward]], whom he characterized as \"not a responsible journalist.\" John Taylor, a spokesman for Nixon, overturned Hewitt's decision after two days.<ref>{{cite book |title=Watergate in American Memory: How We Remember, Forget, and Reconstruct the Past\n |author=Michael Schudson |publisher=Basic Books |year=1992 |isbn=0-465-09083-4\n | url=https://archive.org/details/watergateinameri0000schu|url-access=registration\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/watergateinameri0000schu/page/196 196]\n |quote=Hugh-Hewitt.\n }}</ref> It became the subject of editorial rebuke in ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/31/magazine/hugh-hewitt-doesnt-care-for-billionaires.html|title=Hugh Hewitt Doesn\u2019t Care for Billionaires|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHewitt left the Nixon Library in 1990 to practice law, and began a weekend radio talk show for the [[Los Angeles]] radio station [[KFI]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2015/09/hugh-hewitt-donald-trump-213146|title=Donald Trump\u2019s Grand Inquisitor|last=Purdum|first=Todd S.|website=POLITICO Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> where he broadcast until 1995. In the spring of 1992, he began co-hosting L.A. [[PBS]] member station [[KCET]]'s nightly news and public affairs program, ''[[Life & Times (TV series)|Life & Times]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcet.org/kcet-50th-anniversary/january-1992-kcets-signature-news-program-life-times-debuts|title=January 1992 - KCET's Signature News Program 'Life & Times' Debuts|last=Trinidad|first=Elson|date=2014-09-02|website=KCET|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> and remained with the program until the fall of 2001, when he began broadcasting his own radio show in the afternoons. Hewitt received three [[Emmy Awards|Emmys]] for his work on ''Life & Times'' on KCET,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hindman|first=Matthew|title=The Myth of Digital Democracy|publisher=|year=2009|isbn=|location=|pages=116}}</ref> and also conceived and hosted the 1996 PBS series ''Searching for God in America.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1996-07-05-ca-21260-story.html|title='Life' Host Goes on Search for 'God in America'|date=1996-07-05|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nHe used to be a weekly columnist for the ''Daily Standard''<ref>{{Cite book|last=BusinessNews Publishing|first=|title=Summary: Blog: Review and Analysis of Hugh Hewitt\u00b4s Book|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> (the online edition of ''[[The Weekly Standard]]'') and ''[[World (magazine)|World]]''. He also occasionally appears as a political/social commentator on programs such as ''The [[Dennis Miller]] Show'', ''[[Hardball with Chris Matthews]]'', ''[[Larry King Live]]'', ''[[The O'Reilly Factor]]'' and ''[[Today (NBC program)|The Today Show]]''. On April 24, 2006, Hewitt appeared as a guest on ''[[The Colbert Report]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.colbertnewshub.com/episode-guide/the-colbert-report/episode-guides-2006/april-2006/|title=April 2006|date=2015-01-07|website=www.colbertnewshub.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nHewitt has been criticized by [[Andrew Sullivan]], who calls him a \"Christianist.\"<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://hughhewitt.townhall.com/g/f00239bd-029d-45d4-b721-e58170b0bfd0\n |title       = Sullivan Fatigue\n |author      = Hugh Hewitt\n |date        = August 5, 2006\n |accessdate  = March 26, 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080820132130/http://hughhewitt.townhall.com/g/f00239bd-029d-45d4-b721-e58170b0bfd0\n |archivedate = August 20, 2008\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\nWhen Sullivan appeared on Hewitt's radio show to promote his book ''The Conservative Soul,'' a lively exchange ensued and Hewitt criticized Sullivan's book as intellectually messy.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.hughhewitt.com/transcripts.aspx?id=1f05feeb-8739-495d-befb-5617d890b118 |title=Transcript of ''Hugh Hewitt Show'': Andrew Sullivan on ''The Conservative Soul''\n|date=October 25, 2006 |accessdate=March 26, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHewitt also became a Professor of Law at Chapman University School of Law during that time. He currently teaches [[constitutional law]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.chapman.edu/our-faculty/hugh-hewitt\n |title=Hugh Hewitt |work=Chapman University School of Law: Law Faculty\n |accessdate = August 11, 2016}}</ref>\nIn addition to his contributions as a professor, Hewitt founded and continues to guide the legal scholarship of the ''Nexus Journal of Law and Policy''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chapman.edu/our-faculty/faculty-directory.aspx|title=Faculty Profile|website=www.chapman.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Janiskee|first=Brian P.|title=The California Republic: Institutions, Statesmanship, and Policies|last2=Masugi|first2=Ken|publisher=|year=2004|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Hewitt returned to the Nixon Library as president and CEO of the [[Richard Nixon Foundation]], the nonprofit that co-operates the Nixon Library with the [[National Archives and Records Administration]]. On his first day in the job, Hewitt announced that he would split his time between Orange County and Washington, D.C. and open a Nixon Foundation office in Washington.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.nixonfoundation.org/2019/07/release-hugh-hewitt-announces-new-events-board-members/\n |title=Hewitt Announces New Events, Board Members, More |work=Richard Nixon Foundation\n |accessdate = August 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Broadcasts ==\n=== ''The Hugh Hewitt Show'' (radio) ===\nHewitt's nationally syndicated radio show, ''The Hugh Hewitt Show'', is broadcast from California from 6 to 9 am ET on weekdays. The show appears on more than 75 stations<ref>{{cite web\n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = Hugh Hewitt Show \u2013 all stations and times\n  | work =\n  | publisher = TuneIn Radio\n  | date =\n  | url = http://tunein.com/radio/options/Hugh-Hewitt-Show-p33383/\n  | doi =\n  | accessdate = August 11, 2016\n}}</ref> and is syndicated by the [[Salem Radio Network]]. Beginning April 4, 2016, the show moved to a morning [[drive time]] slot.<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hugh-hewitt-larry-elder-salem-879432 Hugh Hewitt, Larry Elder in Salem Radio Network Shake-Up] Hollywood Reporter. March 30, 2016.</ref> Although Hewitt's background is in law, government, and politics, he also covers American cultural trends and the entertainment industry. He frequently critiques the mainstream media on air, often inviting journalists to defend their work on the show. His regular contributors include law professors [[John C. Eastman]], former Dean of [[Chapman University School of Law]], and [[Erwin Chemerinsky]], Dean of [[UC Irvine Law School]] (whom Hewitt calls \"The Smart Guys\"), [[James Lileks]], [[Mark Steyn]], United States Naval Academy English professor David Allen White (who does a monthly Shakespeare showcase),{{update after|2011|05|14}} and Congressman [[David Dreier]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-CA), as well as frequent callers from around the country. He used to spend the 15th hour of the week discussing movies with \"Emmett of the Unblinking Eye\".\n\n=== ''Hugh Hewitt'' (television) ===\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name      = Hugh Hewitt\n|italic_title   = no<!-- Because it's only part of the Hugh Hewitt article -->\n|image          = \n|caption        =\n|show_name_2    =\n|genre          = Political news/opinion program\n|creator        =\n|writer         =\n|director       = \n|creat_director =\n|developer      =\n|presenter      = Hugh Hewitt\n|starring       =\n|voices         =\n|narrated       =\n|theme_music_composer =\n|opentheme      =\n|endtheme       =\n|composer       =\n|country        = United States\n|language       = English\n|num_seasons    =\n|num_episodes   = \n|list_episodes  =\n|executive_producer = \n|co_exec        =\n|producer       =\n|sup_producer   =\n|asst_producer  =\n|cons_producer  =\n|co-producer    =\n|editor         =\n|story_editor   =\n|location       = \n|cinematography =\n|camera         = \n|runtime        = 30 minutes\n|channel        = [[MSNBC]]\n|picture_format = [[480i]] ([[SDTV]])<br>[[1080i]] ([[HDTV]])\n|audio_format   =\n|first_run      =\n|first_aired    = {{Start date|2017|06|24}}\n|last_aired     = {{End date|2018|06|30}}\n|preceded_by    =\n|followed_by    =\n|related        =\n|website        = \n|production_website =\n}}\nOn June 24, 2017, ''Hugh Hewitt'' debuted, a half-hour television show which ran on MSNBC in the Saturdays 8 a.m. EST timeslot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-hugh-hewitt-20170622-story.html|title=Conservative commentator Hugh Hewitt gets a show in MSNBC's weekend expansion|first=Stephen|last=Battaglio|website=latimes.com}}</ref> On the show, he conducted interviews and provided commentary on current events.<ref>{{cite web |title=About the Show |website=MSNBC}}</ref> On Saturday, June 30, 2018, Hewitt announced that the show had been cancelled, but that he would continue his commentary on the NBC family of networks.<ref>{{cite web\n | url=https://www.rawstory.com/2018/06/conservative-hugh-hewitt-makes-surprise-announcement-msnbc-pulled-plug-show/\n | title=Conservative Hugh Hewitt makes surprise announcement MSNBC has pulled plug on his show\n | publisher=Raw Story\n | date=June 30, 2018\n | accessdate=June 30, 2018\n | first=Bob\n | last=Brigham\n}}</ref>\n\n== Political views ==\nHewitt has described [[George Will]] and [[Charles Krauthammer]] as models for his style of punditry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2016/02/03/hugh-hewitt-wanted-man-go--gop-pundit/79652684/|title=Hugh Hewitt is wanted man as go-to GOP pundit|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en}}</ref> ''Politico'' described Hewitt as an \"ardent Reaganite\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Defense Spending === \nHewitt has advocated for increasing the defense budget in the United States, stating that \"any Republicans who vote against higher defense spending should be fired.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/any-republicans-who-vote-against-higher-defense-spending-should-be-fired|title=Any Republicans who vote against higher defense spending should be fired|date=March 22, 2015|website=Washington Examiner}}</ref>\n\n=== War ===\nIn an interview on [[CNN]] with Anderson Cooper, Hewitt said that in regards to [[George W. Bush]]'s decisions while President, the [[War in Iraq]] would go down as \"one of the wisest he has made.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0603/21/acd.02.html|title=CNN.com - Transcripts|website=edition.cnn.com}}</ref> In regards to the [[Syrian Civil War]], Hewitt stated that President Donald J. Trump was making a \"major error\" in deciding to draw down the number of U.S. troops in the country, over seven years after the beginning of the conflict. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jewishworldreview.com/1218/hewitt122118.php3|title=Hugh Hewitt - In withdrawing from Syria, Trump makes a major error|first=Jewish World|last=Review|website=Jewish World Review}}</ref>\n\n===  Donald Trump ===\nHewitt participated in several of the 2016 Republican primary debates, where he clashed with [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/12/wolf-blitzer-hugh-hewitt-gop-debate-216832|title=Blitzer, Hewitt contain GOP's barroom brawl|last1=Gold|first1=Hadas|authorlink=Hadas Gold|date=December 15, 2015|accessdate=October 2, 2016|website=Politico}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/03/10/politics/republican-debate/|title=Everything you need to know about CNN's GOP debate|last1=Diaz|first1=Daniella|work=CNN|accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref> Hewitt said that Trump did not possess \"the temperament to be president\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2018/04/02/trump-john-bolton-hugh-hewitt-podcast-217770|title=Some Rare Praise for Trump\u2019s National Security Purge|work=POLITICO Magazine|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref> In February 2016, Hewitt wrote that, despite being repeatedly publicly insulted by Trump, he would support him should he become the Republican nominee for president.<ref name=\"Examiner28Feb\">{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/six-reasons-trump-is-still-better-than-clinton/article/2584476|title=Six reasons Trump is still better than Clinton|last=Hewitt|first=Hugh|date=February 28, 2016|work=Washington Examiner|accessdate=February 28, 2016}}</ref> In June 2016, after Trump's controversial remarks concerning Judge [[Gonzalo Curiel]], Hewitt publicly called on the [[Republican National Committee|RNC]] to disendorse Trump as nominee. A week later, Hewitt reversed his position in a ''Washington Post'' op-ed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/hugh-hewitt-donald-trump_us_5762bdd2e4b0df4d586f6505|title=Hugh Hewitt Decides To Back Donald Trump After All|last1=Levine|first1=Sam|date=June 16, 2016|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref> Internal emails showed that a Salem Media executive pressured Hewitt to support Trump, and that the Salem Media executive attributed Hewitt's support for Trump in the aforementioned ''Washington Post'' op-ed shortly after to the pressure.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/05/09/media/salem-radio-executives-trump/index.html|title=Salem executives pressured radio hosts to cover Trump more positively, emails show|last=Darcy|first=Hadas Gold and Oliver|work=CNNMoney|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref> Hewitt denied being pressured to change his position on Trump.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nOn August 3, he publicly floated the idea of replacing Donald with [[Ivanka Trump]] on the ticket.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://theweek.com/speedreads/641132/trump-supporter-hugh-hewitt-floats-replacing-donald-ivanka-win-over-nevertrumpers|title=Trump supporter Hugh Hewitt floats replacing Donald with Ivanka to win over #NeverTrumpers|date=August 4, 2016|work=The Week|accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref> On October 8, he called on Trump to drop out of the race because of a [[Donald Trump and Billy Bush recording|controversial recording of Trump]] that was published the previous day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/10/hugh-hewitt-donald-trump-229350|title=Conservative radio host Hugh Hewitt calls on Trump to quit|last1=Politico Staff|date=October 8, 2016|work=POLITICO|accessdate=October 8, 2016}}</ref> Hewitt has said he ultimately voted for Trump.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hughhewitt.com/dear-president-elect-trump/|title=Dear President-Elect Trump... The Hugh Hewitt Show|date=November 9, 2016|work=The Hugh Hewitt Show|accessdate=November 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHewitt supported Trump's decision to re-shuffle his foreign policy staff in March\u2013April 2018, and place John Bolton and Mike Pompeo in key national security positions.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2018/04/trump-doctrine-foreign-policy/556778/|title=Trumpism: Speak Loudly and Carry a Big Stick|last=Friedman|first=Uri|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> He described John Bolton, a nationalist hawk, as \"peace-through-strength, 600-[Navy] ship, Reagan conservative\".<ref name=\":3\" /> According to ''Politico'', Hewitt emerged \"perhaps the most public advocate for Trump\u2019s hawkish new national security team at a time when others, even inside his own party, have voiced increasing fears that Trump is surrounding himself with war-minded hawks who may play to the president\u2019s worst instincts.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAmid the Trump-Ukraine scandal, which led to the impeachment of President Trump, Hewitt floated a conspiracy theory that the whistleblower complaint that set off the scandal was by a whistleblower who was trying to divert attention from his own involvement in a \"Clintons-Obama-Biden collusion debacle\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/09/gop-divided-by-whistleblower-complaint-on-trump-and-ukraine.html|title=GOP Divided Over How Enthusiastically to Cover for Trump\u2019s Corruption on Ukraine|last=Levitz|first=Eric|date=2019-09-26|website=Intelligencer|language=en-us|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2019/09/trump-and-his-right-wing-allies-are-losing-their-minds-over-the-whistleblower-complaint/|title=Trump and his right-wing allies are losing their minds over the whistleblower complaint|last=Spinelli|first=Dan|website=Mother Jones|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> He penned an op-ed about the impeachment inquiry titled, \"Impeachment-minded Democrats, welcome to Al Capone\u2019s vault. Look familiar?\"<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/trump-impeachment-inquiry/hugh-hewitt-descends-further-pro-trump-fever-swamps-mainstream-media|title=Hugh Hewitt descends further into pro-Trump fever swamps as mainstream media continue to legitimize him|last=Kleefeld|first=Eric|website=Media Matters for America|language=en|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2019/09/26/impeachment-minded-democrats-welcome-al-capones-vault-look-familiar/|title=Impeachment-minded Democrats, welcome to Al Capone\u2019s vault. Look familiar?|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He said that the FBI had tried a \"coup\" against Trump and that Democrats were trying \"another coup\".<ref name=\":7\" /> He described the phone call where Trump requests that the Ukrainian President investigate Joe Biden, a 2020 Democratic presidential candidate, as a \"nothingburger.\"<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" />\n\nIn October 2019, Hewitt defended Trump's decision to remove a small contingent of US military forces from Northern Syria where they served as a buffer between Turkey and Syrian Kurds, leaving Kurds vulnerable to attack by Turkish forces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ocweekly.com/ocs-own-hugh-hewitt-cheers-trumps-abandonment-of-kurdish-forces/|title=OC\u2019s Own Hugh Hewitt Cheers Trump\u2019s Abandonment of Kurdish Forces|last=Rom\u00e1n|first=Gabriel San|date=2019-10-09|website=OC Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Immigration ===\nIn a June 2018 interview with Attorney General Jeff Sessions, Hewitt repeatedly pressed Sessions about the morality of the Trump administration's decision to separate undocumented immigrant children from their parents.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2018/06/05/sessions-defends-separating-immigrant-parents-and-children-weve-got-to-get-this-message-out/|title=Sessions defends separating immigrant parents and children: \u2018We\u2019ve got to get this message out\u2019|last=Rosenberg|first=Eli|date=2018-06-05|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-06-07|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Hewitt said, \"I don\u2019t think children should be separated from biological parents at any age, but especially if they\u2019re infants and toddlers. I think it\u2019s traumatic and terribly difficult on the child.\"<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n=== Media ===\nA recurring theme on Hewitt's show is accusing the mainstream media of liberal bias and lack of transparency.<ref name=\"Lemann2005\">{{cite news\n |url=http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2005/08/29/050829fa_fact_lemann \n |title=Right Hook \n |publisher=[[The New Yorker]] \n |page=34 \n |author=[[Nicholas Lemann]] \n |date=August 29, 2005 \n |accessdate=March 26, 2008 \n}} ([https://web.archive.org/web/20061011210637/http://media.salemwebnetwork.com/Townhall/pdf/newyorker.pdf Scanned copy (archived October 11, 2006)])</ref>\n\n=== Scott Pruitt ===\nIn April 2018, Hewitt defended EPA Administrator Scott Pruitt amid controversy over his expenditures as Administrator and a conflict of interest over renting a condo at discounted prices from a lobbyist representing clients regulated by the EPA.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/381392-ex-bush-ethics-lawyer-confronts-hugh-hewitt-over-pruitt-ethics-this|title=Ex-Bush ethics lawyer confronts Hugh Hewitt over Pruitt ethics: \u2018This is corruption\u2019|last=Bowden|first=John|date=2018-04-03|work=TheHill|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en}}</ref> ''Politico'' described Hewitt as \"one of Pruitt's staunchest defenders\".<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/07/pruitt-california-cleanup-hewitt-meeting-521215|title=Pruitt fast-tracked California cleanup after Hugh Hewitt brokered meeting|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-05-08}}</ref> Hewitt described the numerous ethics scandals facing Pruitt as \"nonsense scandals\" and argued that Pruitt's critics were \"just trying to stop the deregulation effort\".<ref name=\":4\" /> Hewitt argued that the top EPA ethics official had approved Pruitt's rental arrangement and that it therefore did not constitute a gift.<ref name=\":0\" /> Richard Painter, ethics lawyer in the George W. Bush administration, argued against Hewitt, saying it was a \"violation of the gift rules, and no ethics lawyer could cover that up\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHewitt has argued that media coverage of Pruitt has been \"hyperpartisan\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/combative-but-not-cruel-mr-president/2017/07/04/6af74d86-60ad-11e7-8adc-fea80e32bf47_story.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Combative, but not cruel, Mr. President|last=Hewitt|first=Hugh|date=2017-07-04|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> In an interview with Pruitt, Hewitt said \"I know you are not a climate denier\"; Pruitt rejects the [[Scientific opinion on climate change|scientific consensus on climate change]].<ref name=\":1\" /> After Pruitt resigned amid a dozen separate ethics investigations, Hewitt defended Pruitt, saying he \"is a good friend and a very good man, caricatured by left and MSM. I hope he sets to work on a memoir ASAP and deals out a tenth of what he took.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2018/07/05/scott-pruitt-resignation-hollywood-takes-parting-shots-epa-boss/761302002/|title=Scott Pruitt resignation: Hollywood takes a few parting shots at scandal-plagued EPA chief|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2018-07-05|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/minutes/149649/scott-pruitt-will-always-hero-right-wing-fans|title=Scott Pruitt will always be a hero to his right-wing fans.|work=The New Republic|access-date=2018-07-05|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nHugh Hewitt's son, James, is a political appointee working under Pruitt.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motherjones.com/environment/2017/07/scott-pruitt-desperately-wants-to-be-loved/|title=Scott Pruitt desperately wants to be loved|work=Mother Jones|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> In May 2018, it was reported that Pruitt had personally prioritized a polluted [[Orange County, California|Orange County]] site for immediate and intense clean-up via long-term federal clean-up funding after Hewitt had brokered a December 2017 meeting between Pruitt and a legal firm representing the polluted district.<ref name=\":4\" /> The EPA did not disclose the meeting; it was revealed after a Freedom of Information Act lawsuit.<ref name=\":4\" /> Hewitt lived in Orange County for over two decades before relocating to Virginia in 2015; he is employed by the law firm.<ref name=\":4\" /> After the meeting, Hewitt would frequently defend Pruitt amid a number of ethics scandals.<ref name=\":4\" /> [[Fred Hiatt]], the editorial page editor at the ''Washington Post'', where Hewitt is a contributing columnist, said that he was \"disturbed\" by the reports of Hewitt's undisclosed ties, and that Hewitt would not write on issues related to the EPA again.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/msnbc-under-fire-host-hugh-hewitt-helped-broker-meeting-epa-leader-1109750|title=MSNBC Under Fire After Host Hugh Hewitt Helped Broker Meeting With EPA Leader|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-05-09|language=en}}</ref> MSNBC gave Hewitt a verbal warning after he failed to disclose the EPA meeting to viewers of his MSNBC show.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/msnbc-warned-host-hugh-hewitt-epa-meeting-revelation-1110207|title=MSNBC Verbally Warned Host Hugh Hewitt About Standards Violation After EPA Meeting Reveal|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-05-09|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===CNN Debate===\nHewitt was booed during a [[CNN]] debate in 2015 for his controversial questioning of presidential candidate [[Ben Carson]]. He asked whether Carson was capable of ordering \"ruthless\" military strikes that could kill thousands of innocent children.<ref name=\"time-debate-ref\">{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/4150910/republican-debate-ben-carson-isis/|title=Audience Boos as Ben Carson Asked About Bombing Children|website=Time}}</ref> Following Carson's initial answer to the question, Hewitt asked Carson to confirm whether he was, in fact, \"OK with the death of thousands of innocent children and civilians.\" The audience subsequently booed Hewitt.<ref name=\"time-debate-ref\"></ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/blogs/live-from-the-venetian/2015/12/hugh-hewitt-ben-carson-innocent-children-war-216820|title=Hugh Hewitt booed after pressing Ben Carson|first=Hadas|last=Gold|website=POLITICO}}</ref>\n\n== Books ==\n* '' The Queen: The Epic Ambition of Hillary and the Coming of a Second \"Clinton Era\"'' (2015, {{ISBN|1-4555-6251-3}})\n* ''The Happiest Life: Seven Gifts, Seven Givers, and the Secret to Genuine Success'' (2013, {{ISBN|1-5955-5578-1}})\n* ''The Brief Against Obama: The Rise, Fall & Epic Fail of the Hope & Change Presidency'' (2012,  {{ISBN|1-4555-1630-9}})\n*''The War Against the West: Crucial Conversations with the Most Informed Experts About Our Enemies, Our Defenses, Our Strategy and Our Leaders in the Long War Against Islamist Extremism'' (2008, {{ISBN|978-1-60791-069-5}})\n*''A Mormon in the White House?: 10 Things Every American Should Know about Mitt Romney'' (2007,  {{ISBN|1-59698-502-X}})\n* ''A Guide to Christian Ambition: Using Career, Politics, and Culture to Influence the World'' (2006, {{ISBN|0-7852-8871-6}})\n* ''Painting the Map Red: The Fight to Create a Permanent Republican Majority'' (2006, {{ISBN|0-89526-002-6}})\n* ''Blog: Understanding the Information Reformation That's Changing Your World'' (2005, {{ISBN|0-7852-8804-X}})\n* ''If It's Not Close, They Can't Cheat: Crushing the Democrats in Every Election and Why Your Life Depends on It'' (2004, {{ISBN|0-7852-6319-5}})\n* ''In, But Not Of: A Guide to Christian Ambition'' (2003, {{ISBN|0-7852-6395-0}})\n* ''The Embarrassed Believer'' (1998, {{ISBN|0-8499-1419-1}})\n* ''Searching for God in America: The Companion Volume to the Acclaimed TV Series'' (1996, {{ISBN|0-7881-9914-5}})\n* ''First Principles: A Primer of Ideas for the College-Bound Student'' (1987, {{ISBN|0-89526-793-4}})\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.hughhewitt.com/}}\n* [http://townhall.com/columnists/hughhewitt/ Hewitt's columns at Townhall.com]\n* {{C-SPAN|Hugh Hewitt}}\n\n{{MSNBC personalities}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hewitt, Hugh}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American alternative journalists]]\n[[Category:American male bloggers]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American conservative talk radio hosts]]\n[[Category:American television journalists]]\n[[Category:Chapman University School of Law faculty]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Irvine, California]]\n[[Category:People from Warren, Ohio]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Journalists from California]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Ohio]]\n[[Category:MSNBC people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{infobox person\n| name               = Hugh Hewitt\n| image              = Hugh Hewitt by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption            = Hewitt speaking in January 2017\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1956|2|22}}\n| birth_place        = [[Warren, Ohio]], U.S.\n| television         = ''Hugh Hewitt''\n| alma_mater         = [[Harvard University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[University of Michigan]] {{small|([[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n| party              = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| residence          = [[Orange, California]], U.S.\n| home_town           = [[Warren, Ohio]], U.S.\n| occupation         = Radio talk show host, lawyer, law professor, [[Television presenter|Television host]], political commentator, author\n| employer           = [[Salem Radio Network]]<br>[[NBC News]]/[[MSNBC]]<br>[[Chapman University School of Law]]<br>[[Richard Nixon Foundation]]\n| years_active       = 1983\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Betsy Hewitt|1982}}\n}}\n\n'''Hugh Hewitt''' (born February 22, 1956) is an American radio talk show host with the [[Salem Radio Network]] and an attorney, [[academic]], and author. Generally a [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]], he writes about law, society, politics, and [[media bias in the United States]]. Hewitt is President and CEO of the [[Richard Nixon Foundation]], a law professor at [[Chapman University School of Law]], a columnist for the ''[[Washington Post]]'', and a regular political commentator on [[NBC News]] and [[MSNBC]].\n\n== Early life ==\nHewitt is the son of Marguerite (n\u00e9e Rohl) and William Robert Hewitt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ieYTAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA137 |title=The Happiest Life|work=google.ca|accessdate=February 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tributes.com/show/Atty.-William-R.-Hewitt-88199041|title=Atty. Hewitt  Obituary  \u2013 Ohio \u2013 Tributes.com|work=tributes.com|accessdate=February 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://records.ancestry.com/hugh_z_hewitt_records.ashx?pid=129399466|title=Hugh Z Hewitt|work=ancestry.com|accessdate=February 24, 2015}}</ref> He describes himself as \"a descendant of both [[Ulster]] and [[Republic of Ireland|the Republic]] through a green-orange marriage of immigrants from [[County Down]] and [[County Clare]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2019/12/07/free-world-needs-boris-johnson/|title=Opinion &#124; The free world needs Boris Johnson|first=Hugh Hewitt closeHugh|last=HewittBioBioFollowFollow|website=Washington Post}}</ref> He attended [[John F. Kennedy High School (Warren, Ohio)|John F. Kennedy Catholic High School]]<ref>[http://www.warrenjfk.com/?page=alumgolden Golden Eagle Alumni Award] John F. Kennedy Catholic School</ref> in [[Warren, Ohio]], and [[Harvard College|Harvard University]], and graduated ''[[cum laude]]'' with a [[Bachelors of Arts|B.A.]] in government in 1978. After leaving Harvard, he worked as a ghostwriter for [[Richard Nixon]] in [[California]] and [[New York (state)|New York]], before studying at the [[University of Michigan Law School]], where he was inducted into the [[Order of the Coif]]. Hewitt received his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree in 1983, then moved to [[Washington D.C.]] to clerk for Judges [[Roger Robb]] and [[George MacKinnon]] on the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit]] in 1983\u201384.\n\nHewitt worked in many posts in the [[Ronald Reagan|Reagan]] administration, including Deputy Director and General Counsel of the [[United States Office of Personnel Management|Office of Personnel Management]], General Counsel for the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]], Assistant [[White House Counsel]] and Special Assistant to the [[United States Attorney General|Attorney General]].<ref>[http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=35466 Nomination of Hugh Hewitt To Be Deputy Director of the Office of Personnel Management] The American Presidency Project.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHewitt returned to California in 1989 to oversee construction of the [[Richard Nixon Presidential Library and Museum]] as the library's executive director from groundbreaking through dedication and opening.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/socal/daily-pilot/entertainment/tn-wknd-et-nixon-20190328-story.html|title=Conservative commentator Hugh Hewitt to become president of the Richard Nixon Foundation|date=2019-03-27|website=Daily Pilot|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> In 1990, Hewitt sparked controversy by proposing screening of researchers wishing to use the library resources. Hewitt suggested refusing admission to researchers deemed \"unfriendly\" \u2013 specifically [[Bob Woodward]], whom he characterized as \"not a responsible journalist.\" John Taylor, a spokesman for Nixon, overturned Hewitt's decision after two days.<ref>{{cite book |title=Watergate in American Memory: How We Remember, Forget, and Reconstruct the Past\n |author=Michael Schudson |publisher=Basic Books |year=1992 |isbn=0-465-09083-4\n | url=https://archive.org/details/watergateinameri0000schu|url-access=registration\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/watergateinameri0000schu/page/196 196]\n |quote=Hugh-Hewitt.\n }}</ref> It became the subject of editorial rebuke in ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/31/magazine/hugh-hewitt-doesnt-care-for-billionaires.html|title=Hugh Hewitt Doesn\u2019t Care for Billionaires|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHewitt left the Nixon Library in 1990 to practice law, and began a weekend radio talk show for the [[Los Angeles]] radio station [[KFI]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2015/09/hugh-hewitt-donald-trump-213146|title=Donald Trump\u2019s Grand Inquisitor|last=Purdum|first=Todd S.|website=POLITICO Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> where he broadcast until 1995. In the spring of 1992, he began co-hosting L.A. [[PBS]] member station [[KCET]]'s nightly news and public affairs program, ''[[Life & Times (TV series)|Life & Times]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcet.org/kcet-50th-anniversary/january-1992-kcets-signature-news-program-life-times-debuts|title=January 1992 - KCET's Signature News Program 'Life & Times' Debuts|last=Trinidad|first=Elson|date=2014-09-02|website=KCET|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> and remained with the program until the fall of 2001, when he began broadcasting his own radio show in the afternoons. Hewitt received three [[Emmy Awards|Emmys]] for his work on ''Life & Times'' on KCET,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hindman|first=Matthew|title=The Myth of Digital Democracy|publisher=|year=2009|isbn=|location=|pages=116}}</ref> and also conceived and hosted the 1996 PBS series ''Searching for God in America.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1996-07-05-ca-21260-story.html|title='Life' Host Goes on Search for 'God in America'|date=1996-07-05|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nHe used to be a weekly columnist for the ''Daily Standard''<ref>{{Cite book|last=BusinessNews Publishing|first=|title=Summary: Blog: Review and Analysis of Hugh Hewitt\u00b4s Book|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> (the online edition of ''[[The Weekly Standard]]'') and ''[[World (magazine)|World]]''. He also occasionally appears as a political/social commentator on programs such as ''The [[Dennis Miller]] Show'', ''[[Hardball with Chris Matthews]]'', ''[[Larry King Live]]'', ''[[The O'Reilly Factor]]'' and ''[[Today (NBC program)|The Today Show]]''. On April 24, 2006, Hewitt appeared as a guest on ''[[The Colbert Report]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.colbertnewshub.com/episode-guide/the-colbert-report/episode-guides-2006/april-2006/|title=April 2006|date=2015-01-07|website=www.colbertnewshub.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nHewitt has been criticized by [[Andrew Sullivan]], who calls him a \"Christianist.\"<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://hughhewitt.townhall.com/g/f00239bd-029d-45d4-b721-e58170b0bfd0\n |title       = Sullivan Fatigue\n |author      = Hugh Hewitt\n |date        = August 5, 2006\n |accessdate  = March 26, 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080820132130/http://hughhewitt.townhall.com/g/f00239bd-029d-45d4-b721-e58170b0bfd0\n |archivedate = August 20, 2008\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\nWhen Sullivan appeared on Hewitt's radio show to promote his book ''The Conservative Soul,'' a lively exchange ensued and Hewitt criticized Sullivan's book as intellectually messy.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.hughhewitt.com/transcripts.aspx?id=1f05feeb-8739-495d-befb-5617d890b118 |title=Transcript of ''Hugh Hewitt Show'': Andrew Sullivan on ''The Conservative Soul''\n|date=October 25, 2006 |accessdate=March 26, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHewitt also became a Professor of Law at Chapman University School of Law during that time. He currently teaches [[constitutional law]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.chapman.edu/our-faculty/hugh-hewitt\n |title=Hugh Hewitt |work=Chapman University School of Law: Law Faculty\n |accessdate = August 11, 2016}}</ref>\nIn addition to his contributions as a professor, Hewitt founded and continues to guide the legal scholarship of the ''Nexus Journal of Law and Policy''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chapman.edu/our-faculty/faculty-directory.aspx|title=Faculty Profile|website=www.chapman.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Janiskee|first=Brian P.|title=The California Republic: Institutions, Statesmanship, and Policies|last2=Masugi|first2=Ken|publisher=|year=2004|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Hewitt returned to the Nixon Library as President and CEO of the [[Richard Nixon Foundation]], the nonprofit that co-operates the Nixon Library with the [[National Archives and Records Administration]]. On his first day in the job, Hewitt announced that he would split his time between Orange County and Washington, D.C. and open a Nixon Foundation office in Washington.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.nixonfoundation.org/2019/07/release-hugh-hewitt-announces-new-events-board-members/\n |title=Hewitt Announces New Events, Board Members, More |work=Richard Nixon Foundation\n |accessdate = August 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Broadcasts ==\n=== ''The Hugh Hewitt Show'' (radio) ===\nHewitt's nationally syndicated radio show, ''The Hugh Hewitt Show'', is broadcast from California from 6 to 9 am ET on weekdays. The show appears on more than 75 stations<ref>{{cite web\n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = Hugh Hewitt Show \u2013 all stations and times\n  | work =\n  | publisher = TuneIn Radio\n  | date =\n  | url = http://tunein.com/radio/options/Hugh-Hewitt-Show-p33383/\n  | doi =\n  | accessdate = August 11, 2016\n}}</ref> and is syndicated by the [[Salem Radio Network]]. Beginning April 4, 2016, the show moved to a morning [[drive time]] slot.<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hugh-hewitt-larry-elder-salem-879432 Hugh Hewitt, Larry Elder in Salem Radio Network Shake-Up] Hollywood Reporter. March 30, 2016.</ref> Although Hewitt's background is in law, government, and politics, he also covers American cultural trends and the entertainment industry. He frequently critiques the mainstream media on air, often inviting journalists to defend their work on the show. His regular contributors include law professors [[John C. Eastman]], former Dean of [[Chapman University School of Law]], and [[Erwin Chemerinsky]], Dean of [[UC Irvine Law School]] (whom Hewitt calls \"The Smart Guys\"), [[James Lileks]], [[Mark Steyn]], United States Naval Academy English professor David Allen White (who does a monthly Shakespeare showcase),{{update after|2011|05|14}} and Congressman [[David Dreier]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-CA), as well as frequent callers from around the country. He used to spend the 15th hour of the week discussing movies with \"Emmett of the Unblinking Eye\".\n\n=== ''Hugh Hewitt'' (television) ===\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name      = Hugh Hewitt\n|italic_title   = no<!-- Because it's only part of the Hugh Hewitt article -->\n|image          = \n|caption        =\n|show_name_2    =\n|genre          = Political news/opinion program\n|creator        =\n|writer         =\n|director       = \n|creat_director =\n|developer      =\n|presenter      = Hugh Hewitt\n|starring       =\n|voices         =\n|narrated       =\n|theme_music_composer =\n|opentheme      =\n|endtheme       =\n|composer       =\n|country        = United States\n|language       = English\n|num_seasons    =\n|num_episodes   = \n|list_episodes  =\n|executive_producer = \n|co_exec        =\n|producer       =\n|sup_producer   =\n|asst_producer  =\n|cons_producer  =\n|co-producer    =\n|editor         =\n|story_editor   =\n|location       = \n|cinematography =\n|camera         = \n|runtime        = 30 minutes\n|channel        = [[MSNBC]]\n|picture_format = [[480i]] ([[SDTV]])<br>[[1080i]] ([[HDTV]])\n|audio_format   =\n|first_run      =\n|first_aired    = {{Start date|2017|06|24}}\n|last_aired     = {{End date|2018|06|30}}\n|preceded_by    =\n|followed_by    =\n|related        =\n|website        = \n|production_website =\n}}\nOn June 24, 2017, ''Hugh Hewitt'' debuted, a half-hour television show which ran on MSNBC in the Saturdays 8 a.m. EST timeslot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-hugh-hewitt-20170622-story.html|title=Conservative commentator Hugh Hewitt gets a show in MSNBC's weekend expansion|first=Stephen|last=Battaglio|website=latimes.com}}</ref> On the show, he conducted interviews and provided commentary on current events.<ref>{{cite web |title=About the Show |website=MSNBC}}</ref> On Saturday, June 30, 2018, Hewitt announced that the show had been cancelled, but that he would continue his commentary on the NBC family of networks.<ref>{{cite web\n | url=https://www.rawstory.com/2018/06/conservative-hugh-hewitt-makes-surprise-announcement-msnbc-pulled-plug-show/\n | title=Conservative Hugh Hewitt makes surprise announcement MSNBC has pulled plug on his show\n | publisher=Raw Story\n | date=June 30, 2018\n | accessdate=June 30, 2018\n | first=Bob\n | last=Brigham\n}}</ref>\n\n== Political views ==\nHewitt has described [[George Will]] and [[Charles Krauthammer]] as models for his style of punditry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2016/02/03/hugh-hewitt-wanted-man-go--gop-pundit/79652684/|title=Hugh Hewitt is wanted man as go-to GOP pundit|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en}}</ref> ''Politico'' described Hewitt as an \"ardent Reaganite\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Defense Spending === \nHewitt has advocated for increasing the defense budget in the United States, stating that \"any Republicans who vote against higher defense spending should be fired.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/any-republicans-who-vote-against-higher-defense-spending-should-be-fired|title=Any Republicans who vote against higher defense spending should be fired|date=March 22, 2015|website=Washington Examiner}}</ref>\n\n=== War ===\nIn an interview on [[CNN]] with Anderson Cooper, Hewitt said that in regards to [[George W. Bush]]'s decisions while President, the [[War in Iraq]] would go down as \"one of the wisest he has made.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0603/21/acd.02.html|title=CNN.com - Transcripts|website=edition.cnn.com}}</ref> In regards to the [[Syrian Civil War]], Hewitt stated that President Donald J. Trump was making a \"major error\" in deciding to draw down the number of U.S. troops in the country, over seven years after the beginning of the conflict. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jewishworldreview.com/1218/hewitt122118.php3|title=Hugh Hewitt - In withdrawing from Syria, Trump makes a major error|first=Jewish World|last=Review|website=Jewish World Review}}</ref>\n\n===  Donald Trump ===\nHewitt participated in several of the 2016 Republican primary debates, where he clashed with [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/12/wolf-blitzer-hugh-hewitt-gop-debate-216832|title=Blitzer, Hewitt contain GOP's barroom brawl|last1=Gold|first1=Hadas|authorlink=Hadas Gold|date=December 15, 2015|accessdate=October 2, 2016|website=Politico}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/03/10/politics/republican-debate/|title=Everything you need to know about CNN's GOP debate|last1=Diaz|first1=Daniella|work=CNN|accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref> Hewitt said that Trump did not possess \"the temperament to be president\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2018/04/02/trump-john-bolton-hugh-hewitt-podcast-217770|title=Some Rare Praise for Trump\u2019s National Security Purge|work=POLITICO Magazine|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref> In February 2016, Hewitt wrote that, despite being repeatedly publicly insulted by Trump, he would support him should he become the Republican nominee for President.<ref name=\"Examiner28Feb\">{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/six-reasons-trump-is-still-better-than-clinton/article/2584476|title=Six reasons Trump is still better than Clinton|last=Hewitt|first=Hugh|date=February 28, 2016|work=Washington Examiner|accessdate=February 28, 2016}}</ref> In June 2016, after Trump's controversial remarks concerning Judge [[Gonzalo Curiel]], Hewitt publicly called on the [[Republican National Committee|RNC]] to disendorse Trump as nominee. A week later, Hewitt reversed his position in a ''Washington Post'' op-ed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/hugh-hewitt-donald-trump_us_5762bdd2e4b0df4d586f6505|title=Hugh Hewitt Decides To Back Donald Trump After All|last1=Levine|first1=Sam|date=June 16, 2016|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref> Internal emails showed that a Salem Media executive pressured Hewitt to support Trump, and that the Salem Media executive attributed Hewitt's support for Trump in the aforementioned ''Washington Post'' op-ed shortly after to the pressure.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/05/09/media/salem-radio-executives-trump/index.html|title=Salem executives pressured radio hosts to cover Trump more positively, emails show|last=Darcy|first=Hadas Gold and Oliver|work=CNNMoney|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref> Hewitt denied being pressured to change his position on Trump.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nOn August 3, he publicly floated the idea of replacing Donald with [[Ivanka Trump]] on the ticket.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://theweek.com/speedreads/641132/trump-supporter-hugh-hewitt-floats-replacing-donald-ivanka-win-over-nevertrumpers|title=Trump supporter Hugh Hewitt floats replacing Donald with Ivanka to win over #NeverTrumpers|date=August 4, 2016|work=The Week|accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref> On October 8, he called on Trump to drop out of the race because of a [[Donald Trump and Billy Bush recording|controversial recording of Trump]] that was published the previous day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/10/hugh-hewitt-donald-trump-229350|title=Conservative radio host Hugh Hewitt calls on Trump to quit|last1=Politico Staff|date=October 8, 2016|work=POLITICO|accessdate=October 8, 2016}}</ref> Hewitt has said he ultimately voted for Trump.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hughhewitt.com/dear-president-elect-trump/|title=Dear President-Elect Trump... The Hugh Hewitt Show|date=November 9, 2016|work=The Hugh Hewitt Show|accessdate=November 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHewitt supported Trump's decision to re-shuffle his foreign policy staff in March\u2013April 2018, and place John Bolton and Mike Pompeo in key national security positions.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2018/04/trump-doctrine-foreign-policy/556778/|title=Trumpism: Speak Loudly and Carry a Big Stick|last=Friedman|first=Uri|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> He described John Bolton, a nationalist hawk, as \"peace-through-strength, 600-[Navy] ship, Reagan conservative\".<ref name=\":3\" /> According to ''Politico'', Hewitt emerged \"perhaps the most public advocate for Trump\u2019s hawkish new national security team at a time when others, even inside his own party, have voiced increasing fears that Trump is surrounding himself with war-minded hawks who may play to the president\u2019s worst instincts.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAmid the Trump-Ukraine scandal, which led to the impeachment of President Trump, Hewitt floated a conspiracy theory that the whistleblower complaint that set off the scandal was by a whistleblower who was trying to divert attention from his own involvement in a \"Clintons-Obama-Biden collusion debacle\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/09/gop-divided-by-whistleblower-complaint-on-trump-and-ukraine.html|title=GOP Divided Over How Enthusiastically to Cover for Trump\u2019s Corruption on Ukraine|last=Levitz|first=Eric|date=2019-09-26|website=Intelligencer|language=en-us|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2019/09/trump-and-his-right-wing-allies-are-losing-their-minds-over-the-whistleblower-complaint/|title=Trump and his right-wing allies are losing their minds over the whistleblower complaint|last=Spinelli|first=Dan|website=Mother Jones|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> He penned an op-ed about the impeachment inquiry titled, \"Impeachment-minded Democrats, welcome to Al Capone\u2019s vault. Look familiar?\"<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/trump-impeachment-inquiry/hugh-hewitt-descends-further-pro-trump-fever-swamps-mainstream-media|title=Hugh Hewitt descends further into pro-Trump fever swamps as mainstream media continue to legitimize him|last=Kleefeld|first=Eric|website=Media Matters for America|language=en|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2019/09/26/impeachment-minded-democrats-welcome-al-capones-vault-look-familiar/|title=Impeachment-minded Democrats, welcome to Al Capone\u2019s vault. Look familiar?|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He said that the FBI had tried a \"coup\" against Trump and that Democrats were trying \"another coup\".<ref name=\":7\" /> He described the phone call where Trump requests that the Ukrainian President investigate Joe Biden, a 2020 Democratic presidential candidate, as a \"nothingburger.\"<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" />\n\nIn October 2019, Hewitt defended Trump's decision to remove a small contingent of US military forces from Northern Syria where they served as a buffer between Turkey and Syrian Kurds, leaving Kurds vulnerable to attack by Turkish forces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ocweekly.com/ocs-own-hugh-hewitt-cheers-trumps-abandonment-of-kurdish-forces/|title=OC\u2019s Own Hugh Hewitt Cheers Trump\u2019s Abandonment of Kurdish Forces|last=Rom\u00e1n|first=Gabriel San|date=2019-10-09|website=OC Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Immigration ===\nIn a June 2018 interview with Attorney General Jeff Sessions, Hewitt repeatedly pressed Sessions about the morality of the Trump administration's decision to separate undocumented immigrant children from their parents.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2018/06/05/sessions-defends-separating-immigrant-parents-and-children-weve-got-to-get-this-message-out/|title=Sessions defends separating immigrant parents and children: \u2018We\u2019ve got to get this message out\u2019|last=Rosenberg|first=Eli|date=2018-06-05|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-06-07|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Hewitt said, \"I don\u2019t think children should be separated from biological parents at any age, but especially if they\u2019re infants and toddlers. I think it\u2019s traumatic and terribly difficult on the child.\"<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n=== Media ===\nA recurring theme on Hewitt's show is accusing the mainstream media of liberal bias and lack of transparency.<ref name=\"Lemann2005\">{{cite news\n |url=http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2005/08/29/050829fa_fact_lemann \n |title=Right Hook \n |publisher=[[The New Yorker]] \n |page=34 \n |author=[[Nicholas Lemann]] \n |date=August 29, 2005 \n |accessdate=March 26, 2008 \n}} ([https://web.archive.org/web/20061011210637/http://media.salemwebnetwork.com/Townhall/pdf/newyorker.pdf Scanned copy (archived October 11, 2006)])</ref>\n\n=== Scott Pruitt ===\nIn April 2018, Hewitt defended EPA Administrator Scott Pruitt amid controversy over his expenditures as Administrator and a conflict of interest over renting a condo at discounted prices from a lobbyist representing clients regulated by the EPA.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/381392-ex-bush-ethics-lawyer-confronts-hugh-hewitt-over-pruitt-ethics-this|title=Ex-Bush ethics lawyer confronts Hugh Hewitt over Pruitt ethics: \u2018This is corruption\u2019|last=Bowden|first=John|date=2018-04-03|work=TheHill|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en}}</ref> ''Politico'' described Hewitt as \"one of Pruitt's staunchest defenders\".<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/07/pruitt-california-cleanup-hewitt-meeting-521215|title=Pruitt fast-tracked California cleanup after Hugh Hewitt brokered meeting|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-05-08}}</ref> Hewitt described the numerous ethics scandals facing Pruitt as \"nonsense scandals\" and argued that Pruitt's critics were \"just trying to stop the deregulation effort\".<ref name=\":4\" /> Hewitt argued that the top EPA ethics official had approved Pruitt's rental arrangement and that it therefore did not constitute a gift.<ref name=\":0\" /> Richard Painter, ethics lawyer in the George W. Bush administration, argued against Hewitt, saying it was a \"violation of the gift rules, and no ethics lawyer could cover that up\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHewitt has argued that media coverage of Pruitt has been \"hyperpartisan\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/combative-but-not-cruel-mr-president/2017/07/04/6af74d86-60ad-11e7-8adc-fea80e32bf47_story.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Combative, but not cruel, Mr. President|last=Hewitt|first=Hugh|date=2017-07-04|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> In an interview with Pruitt, Hewitt said \"I know you are not a climate denier\"; Pruitt rejects the [[Scientific opinion on climate change|scientific consensus on climate change]].<ref name=\":1\" /> After Pruitt resigned amid a dozen separate ethics investigations, Hewitt defended Pruitt, saying he \"is a good friend and a very good man, caricatured by left and MSM. I hope he sets to work on a memoir ASAP and deals out a tenth of what he took.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2018/07/05/scott-pruitt-resignation-hollywood-takes-parting-shots-epa-boss/761302002/|title=Scott Pruitt resignation: Hollywood takes a few parting shots at scandal-plagued EPA chief|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2018-07-05|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/minutes/149649/scott-pruitt-will-always-hero-right-wing-fans|title=Scott Pruitt will always be a hero to his right-wing fans.|work=The New Republic|access-date=2018-07-05|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nHugh Hewitt's son, James, is a political appointee working under Pruitt.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motherjones.com/environment/2017/07/scott-pruitt-desperately-wants-to-be-loved/|title=Scott Pruitt desperately wants to be loved|work=Mother Jones|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> In May 2018, it was reported that Pruitt had personally prioritized a polluted [[Orange County, California|Orange County]] site for immediate and intense clean-up via long-term federal clean-up funding after Hewitt had brokered a December 2017 meeting between Pruitt and a legal firm representing the polluted district.<ref name=\":4\" /> The EPA did not disclose the meeting; it was revealed after a Freedom of Information Act lawsuit.<ref name=\":4\" /> Hewitt lived in Orange County for over two decades before relocating to Virginia in 2015; he is employed by the law firm.<ref name=\":4\" /> After the meeting, Hewitt would frequently defend Pruitt amid a number of ethics scandals.<ref name=\":4\" /> [[Fred Hiatt]], the editorial page editor at the ''Washington Post'', where Hewitt is a contributing columnist, said that he was \"disturbed\" by the reports of Hewitt's undisclosed ties, and that Hewitt would not write on issues related to the EPA again.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/msnbc-under-fire-host-hugh-hewitt-helped-broker-meeting-epa-leader-1109750|title=MSNBC Under Fire After Host Hugh Hewitt Helped Broker Meeting With EPA Leader|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-05-09|language=en}}</ref> MSNBC gave Hewitt a verbal warning after he failed to disclose the EPA meeting to viewers of his MSNBC show.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/msnbc-warned-host-hugh-hewitt-epa-meeting-revelation-1110207|title=MSNBC Verbally Warned Host Hugh Hewitt About Standards Violation After EPA Meeting Reveal|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-05-09|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===CNN Debate===\nHewitt was booed during a [[CNN]] debate in 2015 for his controversial questioning of presidential candidate [[Ben Carson]]. He asked whether Carson was capable of ordering \"ruthless\" military strikes that could kill thousands of innocent children.<ref name=\"time-debate-ref\">{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/4150910/republican-debate-ben-carson-isis/|title=Audience Boos as Ben Carson Asked About Bombing Children|website=Time}}</ref> Following Carson's initial answer to the question, Hewitt asked Carson to confirm whether he was, in fact, \"OK with the death of thousands of innocent children and civilians.\" The audience subsequently booed Hewitt.<ref name=\"time-debate-ref\"></ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/blogs/live-from-the-venetian/2015/12/hugh-hewitt-ben-carson-innocent-children-war-216820|title=Hugh Hewitt booed after pressing Ben Carson|first=Hadas|last=Gold|website=POLITICO}}</ref>\n\n== Books ==\n* '' The Queen: The Epic Ambition of Hillary and the Coming of a Second \"Clinton Era\"'' (2015, {{ISBN|1-4555-6251-3}})\n* ''The Happiest Life: Seven Gifts, Seven Givers, and the Secret to Genuine Success'' (2013, {{ISBN|1-5955-5578-1}})\n* ''The Brief Against Obama: The Rise, Fall & Epic Fail of the Hope & Change Presidency'' (2012,  {{ISBN|1-4555-1630-9}})\n*''The War Against the West: Crucial Conversations with the Most Informed Experts About Our Enemies, Our Defenses, Our Strategy and Our Leaders in the Long War Against Islamist Extremism'' (2008, {{ISBN|978-1-60791-069-5}})\n*''A Mormon in the White House?: 10 Things Every American Should Know about Mitt Romney'' (2007,  {{ISBN|1-59698-502-X}})\n* ''A Guide to Christian Ambition: Using Career, Politics, and Culture to Influence the World'' (2006, {{ISBN|0-7852-8871-6}})\n* ''Painting the Map Red: The Fight to Create a Permanent Republican Majority'' (2006, {{ISBN|0-89526-002-6}})\n* ''Blog: Understanding the Information Reformation That's Changing Your World'' (2005, {{ISBN|0-7852-8804-X}})\n* ''If It's Not Close, They Can't Cheat: Crushing the Democrats in Every Election and Why Your Life Depends on It'' (2004, {{ISBN|0-7852-6319-5}})\n* ''In, But Not Of: A Guide to Christian Ambition'' (2003, {{ISBN|0-7852-6395-0}})\n* ''The Embarrassed Believer'' (1998, {{ISBN|0-8499-1419-1}})\n* ''Searching for God in America: The Companion Volume to the Acclaimed TV Series'' (1996, {{ISBN|0-7881-9914-5}})\n* ''First Principles: A Primer of Ideas for the College-Bound Student'' (1987, {{ISBN|0-89526-793-4}})\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.hughhewitt.com/}}\n* [http://townhall.com/columnists/hughhewitt/ Hewitt's columns at Townhall.com]\n* {{C-SPAN|Hugh Hewitt}}\n\n{{MSNBC personalities}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hewitt, Hugh}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living 