{"title_page": "Western Hemisphere", "text_new": "{{Coord|0|N|90|W|dim:10000000|display=title}}\n\n[[File:Western Hemisphere LamAz.png|thumb|250px|right|The Western Hemisphere]]\n\nThe '''Western Hemisphere''' is a [[geography|geographical]] term<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{citation | title = [[Oxford Dictionary of English]] | edition = 2nd | year = 2006 | place = London, UK | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | page = 2001}}<br>- {{citation | contribution = Western /western%20hemisphere | title = Merriam Webster's Online Dictionary | edition = based on Collegiate vol., 11th | year = 2006 | place = Springfield, MA | publisher = Merriam-Webster}}</ref> for the half of [[Earth]] which lies [[west]] of the [[prime meridian]] (which crosses [[Greenwich]], [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]) and [[east]] of the [[180th meridian|antimeridian]]. The other half is called the [[Eastern Hemisphere]].<ref>{{citation|website=Britannica.com|title=Western Hemisphere|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Western-Hemisphere}}</ref>\n\nAs an example of [[totum pro parte]], the term Western Hemisphere is widely used by the United States government to mean the [[Americas]].<ref>[https://www.state.gov/bureaus-offices/under-secretary-for-political-affairs/bureau-of-western-hemisphere-affairs/ Bureau of Western Hemisphere Affairs], [[United States Department of State]].</ref><ref>[https://www.treasury.gov/about/organizational-structure/offices/Pages/-Western-Hemisphere.aspx Western Hemisphere], [[United States Department of the Treasury]].</ref><ref>[https://ustr.gov/countries-regions/americas Western Hemisphere], [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]].</ref><ref>[https://www.americasquarterly.org/content/joe-biden-western-hemisphere-needs-us-leadership Joe Biden: The Western Hemisphere Needs U.S. Leadership], [[Americas Quarterly]], 17 December 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.justice.gov/criminal-opdat/worldwide-activities/western-hemisphere Western Hemisphere], [[United States Department of Justice]].</ref><ref>[https://www.fas.usda.gov/regions/western-hemisphere Western Hemisphere],HSBC.bitcoin.chikia.isaac [[United States Department of Agriculture]].</ref>HSBC.venmo<ref>Varo[https://www.fws.gov/international/wildlife-without-borders/western-hemisphere/ Western.jetcoin.adorn.monero.paypal Hemisphere]varo.bitcoin.hsbc, [[United States Fish an.dodgecoin.nylas.varo.venmo.litcoin .chikitaisaac123@gmail.com Service.bitcoin.com]].</ref><ref.nylas.venmo.paypa>varo.bylas[https://us.fulbrightonline.org/countries/selectedregion/18 Western Hemispherectomy], [[Fulbright Program]].tether.bitcoin\n.</ref>Varo.com.chikitaisaac123@gmail.com Varo.com.chikitaisaac123@gmail.com\n\n==Geography==\nThe Western Hemisphere consists of the [[Americas]], the western portions of [[Europe]] and [[Africa]], the [[Cape Dezhnev|extreme eastern tip]] of [[Siberia]] ([[Russia]]), numerous territories in [[Oceania]], and a portion of [[Antarctica]], while excluding some of the [[Aleutian Islands]] to the southwest of the [[Alaska|Alaskan]] mainland.\n\nThe center of the Western Hemisphere is located in the [[Pacific Ocean]] at the intersection of the [[90th meridian west]] and the [[Equator]], among the [[Gal\u00e1pagos Islands]]. The nearest land is [[Genovesa Island]] at {{coord|0.316667|N|89.95|W|format=dms|display=inline}}.\n\nThe [[list of highest mountains on Earth|highest mountain]] in the Western Hemisphere is [[Aconcagua]] in the [[Andes]] of [[Argentina]] at {{convert|6960.8|m|ft}}.<ref name=\"UNC-Sigma\">{{cite web|url= http://www.uncu.edu.ar/novedades/index/informe-cientifico-que-estudia-el-aconcagua-el-coloso-de-america-mide-69608-metros|title= Informe cient\u00edfico que estudia el Aconcagua, el Coloso de Am\u00e9rica mide 6960,8 metros|language= Spanish|trans-title= Scientific Report on Aconcagua, the Colossus of America measures 6960,8m|year= 2012|publisher= [[Universidad Nacional de Cuyo]]|accessdate= September 3, 2012|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120908061725/http://www.uncu.edu.ar/novedades/index/informe-cientifico-que-estudia-el-aconcagua-el-coloso-de-america-mide-69608-metros|archivedate= September 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe tallest building or tower in the Western Hemisphere is the CN tower, located in Toronto, Ontario, Canada at {{coord|43|38|33.22|N|79|23|13.41|W|type:landmark|name=CN Tower}}.\n\n===Proposed revision of hemispheric borders===\nIn an attempt to define the Western Hemisphere as the parts of the world which are not part of the [[Old World]], there also exist projections which use the [[20th meridian west]] and the diametrically opposed [[160th meridian east]] to define the hemisphere.<ref name=\":0\">{{citation | last = Olson | first = Judy M | contribution = Projecting the hemisphere | url=https://courseware.e-education.psu.edu/projection/chapter4.html |title=Matching the map projection to the need | editor1-last = Robinson | editor1-first = Arthur H | editor2-last =  Snyder | editor2-first = John P | year = 1997 | place = Bethesda, MD | publisher = Cartography and Geographic Information Society, American Congress on Surveying and Mapping}}.<br>- {{citation | contribution = Western Hemisphere | title =  Merriam-Webster's Geographical Dictionary | edition = 3rd | year = 2001 | place = Springfield, Massachusetts | publisher = Merriam-Webster | page = 1294}}.</ref> This projection excludes the European and African mainlands and a small portion of northeast [[Greenland]], but includes more of eastern Russia and Oceania.\n\n== Sovereign states in both hemispheres ==\n\nBelow is a list of the sovereign states which are in both the Western and Eastern Hemispheres on the [[IERS Reference Meridian]], in order from north to south:\n\n* {{flagdeco|Denmark|size=23px}} [[Denmark]] (due to [[Greenland]] and the [[Faroe Islands]]; mainland Denmark lies entirely in the Eastern Hemisphere).\n* {{flagdeco|Norway|size=23px}} [[Norway]] (due to [[Jan Mayen]]; mainland Norway lies entirely in the Eastern Hemisphere).\n* {{Flagdeco|United Kingdom|size=23px}} [[United Kingdom]], passing through [[Greenwich]], [[London]]. Most of the country is in the Western Hemisphere.\n* {{flagdeco|France|size=23px}} [[France]], passing through [[Puynormand]] ([[Gironde]].) About 1/3 of the country, including cities like [[Nantes]] or [[Bordeaux]], lies in the Western Hemisphere.\n* {{flagdeco|Spain|size=23px}} [[Spain]], passing through [[Castell\u00f3n de la Plana|Castell\u00f3 de la Plana]] ([[Valencian Community]].) Most of Spain, including the capital [[Madrid]], the [[Canary Islands]] and the southern half of its Mediterranean [[territorial waters]], lies in the Western Hemisphere. Spanish, [[Morocco|Moroccan]] and Algerian Mediterranean waters are the only part of the [[Mediterranean Sea]] located in the Western Hemisphere.\n* {{flagdeco|Algeria|size=23px}} [[Algeria]], passing through [[Stidia]]. About 1/4 of the country including [[Oran]], Algeria's second largest city, is in the Western Hemisphere.\n* {{flagdeco|Mali|size=23px}} [[Mali]], passing through the municipal area of [[Gao]]. Most of Mali, including the capital [[Bamako]], lies in the Western Hemisphere.\n* {{flagdeco|Burkina Faso|size=23px}} [[Burkina Faso]], passing through [[Lalgaye Department|Lalgaye]]. Most of the country, including the capital [[Ouagadougou]], is in the Western Hemisphere.\n* {{flagdeco|Ghana|size=23px}} [[Ghana]], passing through [[Tema]]. Most of Ghana, including the capital [[Accra]], lies in the Western Hemisphere.\n* {{flagdeco|Togo|size=23px}} [[Togo]], passing near Tami ([[Savanes Region, Togo|Savanes Region]]).\n\nBelow is a list of the sovereign states which are in both the Western and Eastern Hemispheres along the [[180th meridian]], in order from north to south. With the exception of the United States ([[Wake Island]]), all of them are located on just one side of the [[International Date Line]], which is curved around them.\n\n* {{flagdeco|Russia|size=23px}} [[Russia]] ([[Siberia]], [[Russian Far East|Far East]])\n* {{flagdeco|United States|size=23px}} [[United States]] ([[United States Minor Outlying Islands]], [[Aleutian Islands]], [[Northern Mariana Islands]], [[Guam]])\n* {{flagdeco|Kiribati|size=23px}} [[Kiribati]]\n* {{flagdeco|Tuvalu|size=23px}} [[Tuvalu]]\n* {{flagdeco|Fiji|size=23px}} [[Fiji]]\n* {{flagdeco|New Zealand|size=23px}} [[New Zealand]] ([[Kermadec Islands|Kermadec]] and [[Chatham Islands|Chatham Island]] groups are east of the 180th meridian)\n\nOne sovereign state has territory on both hemispheres, but neither the prime meridian nor the 180th meridian passes through its territory:\n\n* {{flagdeco|Netherlands|size=23px}} [[Kingdom of the Netherlands|Netherlands]] (The islands of the [[Caribbean Netherlands]] lie entirely within the Western Hemisphere while the [[Netherlands|European Netherlands]] lies entirely in the Eastern Hemisphere.)\n\n== Countries and territories in the Western Hemisphere but not in the Americas ==\nThe following countries and territories lie outside the [[Americas]] yet are entirely/mostly or partially within the Western Hemisphere:\n\n{|\n|-\n|valign=top width=33%|\n\n;<big>[[Africa]]</big>\n;<small>Entirely</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Azores|size=23px}} [[Azores]] ([[Portugal]])\n* {{flagdeco|Cape Verde|size=23px}} [[Cape Verde]]\n* {{flagdeco|Gambia|size=23px}} [[Gambia]]\n* {{flagdeco|Guinea|size=23px}} [[Guinea]]\n* {{flagdeco|Guinea-Bissau|size=23px}} [[Guinea-Bissau]]\n* {{flagdeco|Ivory Coast|size=23px}} [[Ivory Coast]]\n* {{flagdeco|Liberia|size=23px}} [[Liberia]]\n* {{flagdeco|Madeira|size=23px}} [[Madeira]] ([[Portugal]])\n* {{flagdeco|Mauritania|size=23px}} [[Mauritania]]\n* {{flagdeco|Morocco|size=23px}} [[Morocco]]\n* {{flagdeco|Saint Helena|size=23px}} [[Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha]] ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flagdeco|Senegal|size=23px}} [[Senegal]]\n* {{flagdeco|Sierra Leone|size=23px}} [[Sierra Leone]]\n* {{flagdeco|Western Sahara|size=23px}} [[Western Sahara]] ([[Political status of Western Sahara|''Disputed'']])\n\n;<small>Mostly</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Burkina Faso|size=23px}} [[Burkina Faso]]\n* {{flagdeco|Ghana|size=23px}} [[Ghana]]\n* {{flagdeco|Mali|size=23px}} [[Mali]]\n\n;<small>Partially</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Algeria|size=23px}} [[Algeria]]\n* {{flagdeco|Togo|size=23px}} [[Togo]]\n\n<br />\n\n;<big>[[Antarctica]]</big> \n;<small>Entirely</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Antarctica|size=23px}} [[Peter I Island]] ([[Antarctic Treaty System|Antarctic Treaty]] signatories / [[Territorial claims in Antarctica|Claimed]] by [[Norway]])\n* {{flagdeco|South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands|size=23px}} [[South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands]] (Administered by the [[United Kingdom]] / Claimed by [[Argentina]]){{dubious|reason = Not part of Antarctica|date=March 2018}}\n* {{flagdeco|Antarctica|size=23px}} [[South Orkney Islands]] ([[Antarctic Treaty System|Antarctic Treaty]] signatories / [[Territorial claims in Antarctica|Claimed]] by the [[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flagdeco|Antarctica|size=23px}} [[South Shetland Islands]] ([[Antarctic Treaty System|Antarctic Treaty]] signatories / [[Territorial claims in Antarctica|Claimed]] by the [[United Kingdom]])\n\n;<small>Partially</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Antarctica|size=23px}} [[Antarctica]] ([[Antarctic Treaty System|Antarctic Treaty]] signatories)\n** {{flagdeco|Antarctica|size=23px}} [[Antarctic Peninsula]] (Entirely){{dubious|reason = Not a territorial entity|date=March 2018}}\n** {{flagdeco|Antarctica|size=23px}} [[East Antarctica]] (Partially){{dubious|reason = Not a territorial entity|date=March 2018}}\n** {{flagdeco|Antarctica|size=23px}} [[West Antarctica]] (Entirely){{dubious|reason = Not a territorial entity|date=March 2018}}\n** {{flagdeco|Antarctica|size=23px}} [[Transantarctic Mountains]] (Entirely){{dubious|reason = Not a territorial entity|date=March 2018}}\n\n|valign=top width=33%|\n\n;<big>[[Asia]]</big>\n;<small>Partially</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Russia|size=23px}} [[Russia]] ([[Siberia]])\n\n<br />\n\n;<big>[[Europe]]</big>\n;<small>Entirely</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Bailiwick of Guernsey|size=23px}} [[Bailiwick of Guernsey]] ([[United Kingdom]])\n** {{flagdeco|Alderney|size=23px}} [[Alderney]]\n** {{flagdeco|Guernsey|size=23px}} [[Guernsey]]\n** {{flagdeco|Sark|size=23px}} [[Sark]]\n* {{flagdeco|Jersey|size=23px}} [[Jersey|Bailiwick of Jersey]] ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flagdeco|Faroe Islands|size=23px}} [[Faroe Islands]] ([[Denmark]])\n* {{flagdeco|Gibraltar|size=23px}} [[Gibraltar]] ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flagdeco|Iceland|size=23px}} [[Iceland]]\n* {{flagdeco|Isle of Man|size=23px}} [[Isle of Man]] ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flagdeco|Jan Mayen|size=23px}} [[Jan Mayen]] ([[Norway]])\n* {{flagdeco|Portugal|size=23px}} [[Portugal]]\n* {{flagdeco|Republic of Ireland|size=23px}} [[Republic of Ireland]]\n* {{flagdeco|United Kingdom|size=23px}} [[Rockall]] ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flagdeco|Shetland|size=23px}} [[Shetland]] ([[United Kingdom]])\n\n;<small>Mostly</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Spain|size=23px}} [[Spain]]\n* {{flagdeco|United Kingdom|size=23px}} [[United Kingdom]]\n** {{flagdeco|England|size=23px}} [[England]] (Mostly)\n** {{flagdeco|United Kingdom|size=23px}} [[Northern Ireland]] (Entirely)\n** {{flagdeco|Scotland|size=23px}} [[Scotland]] (Entirely)\n** {{flagdeco|Wales|size=23px}} [[Wales]] (Entirely)\n\n;<small>Partially</small>\n* {{flagdeco|France|size=23px}} [[France]] ([[Metropolitan France|Metropolitan]])\n\n|valign=top width=33%|\n\n;<big>[[Oceania]]</big>\n;<small>Entirely</small>\n* {{flagdeco|American Samoa|size=23px}} [[American Samoa]] ([[United States]])\n* {{flagdeco|Baker Island|size=23px}} [[Baker Island]] ([[United States]])\n* {{flagdeco|Chatham Islands|size=23px}} [[Chatham Islands]] ([[New Zealand]])\n* {{flagdeco|Clipperton Island|size=23px}} [[Clipperton Island]] ([[France]])\n* {{flagdeco|Cook Islands|size=23px}} [[Cook Islands]] ([[New Zealand]])\n* {{flagdeco|Easter Island|size=23px}} [[Easter Island]] ([[Chile]])\n* {{flagdeco|French Polynesia|size=23px}} [[French Polynesia]] (including [[Tahiti]]) ([[France]])\n* {{flagdeco|Gal\u00e1pagos Islands|size=23px}} [[Gal\u00e1pagos Islands]] ([[Ecuador]])\n* {{flagdeco|Hawaii|size=23px}} [[Hawaii]] ([[United States]])\n* {{flagdeco|Howland Island|size=23px}} [[Howland Island]] ([[United States]])\n* {{flagdeco|Jarvis Island|size=23px}} [[Jarvis Island]] ([[United States]])\n* {{flagdeco|Johnston Atoll|size=23px}} [[Johnston Atoll]] ([[United States]])\n* {{flagdeco|New Zealand|size=23px}} [[Kermadec Islands]] ([[New Zealand]])\n* {{flagdeco|Kingman Reef|size=23px}} [[Kingman Reef]] ([[United States]])\n* {{flagdeco|Midway Atoll|size=23px}} [[Midway Atoll]] ([[United States]])\n* {{flagdeco|Niue|size=23px}} [[Niue]] ([[Realm of New Zealand|New Zealand]])\n* {{flagdeco|Palmyra Atoll|size=23px}} [[Palmyra Atoll]] ([[United States]])\n* {{flagdeco|Pitcairn Islands|size=23px}} [[Pitcairn Islands]] ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flagdeco|Samoa|size=23px}} [[Samoa]]\n* {{flagdeco|Tokelau|size=23px}} [[Tokelau]] ([[New Zealand]])\n* {{flagdeco|Tonga|size=23px}} [[Tonga]]\n\n;<small>Mostly</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Kiribati|size=23px}} [[Kiribati]]\n* {{flagdeco|Wallis and Futuna|size=23px}} [[Wallis and Futuna]] ([[France]])\n\n;<small>Partially</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Fiji|size=23px}} [[Fiji]]\n* {{flagdeco|Tuvalu|size=23px}} [[Tuvalu]]\n\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commonscatinline}}\n\n{{Hemispheres of the Earth}}\n\n[[Category:Western Hemisphere| ]]\n[[Category:Hemispheres of Earth]]\n", "text_old": "{{Coord|0|N|90|W|dim:10000000|display=title}}\n\n[[File:Western Hemisphere LamAz.png|thumb|250px|right|The Western Hemisphere]]\n\nThe '''Western Hemisphere''' is a [[geography|geographical]] term<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{citation | title = [[Oxford Dictionary of English]] | edition = 2nd | year = 2006 | place = London, UK | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | page = 2001}}<br>- {{citation | contribution = Western /western%20hemisphere | title = Merriam Webster's Online Dictionary | edition = based on Collegiate vol., 11th | year = 2006 | place = Springfield, MA | publisher = Merriam-Webster}}</ref> for the half of [[Earth]] which lies [[west]] of the [[prime meridian]] (which crosses [[Greenwich]], [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]) and [[east]] of the [[180th meridian|antimeridian]]. The other half is called the [[Eastern Hemisphere]].<ref>{{citation|website=Britannica.com|title=Western Hemisphere|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Western-Hemisphere}}</ref>\n\nAs an example of [[totum pro parte]], the term Western Hemisphere is widely used by the United States government to mean the [[Americas]].<ref>[https://www.state.gov/bureaus-offices/under-secretary-for-political-affairs/bureau-of-western-hemisphere-affairs/ Bureau of Western Hemisphere Affairs], [[United States Department of State]].</ref><ref>[https://www.treasury.gov/about/organizational-structure/offices/Pages/-Western-Hemisphere.aspx Western Hemisphere], [[United States Department of the Treasury]].</ref><ref>[https://ustr.gov/countries-regions/americas Western Hemisphere], [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]].</ref><ref>[https://www.americasquarterly.org/content/joe-biden-western-hemisphere-needs-us-leadership Joe Biden: The Western Hemisphere Needs U.S. Leadership], [[Americas Quarterly]], 17 December 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.justice.gov/criminal-opdat/worldwide-activities/western-hemisphere Western Hemisphere], [[United States Department of Justice]].</ref><ref>[https://www.fas.usda.gov/regions/western-hemisphere Western Hemisphere], [[United States Department of Agriculture]].</ref><ref>[https://www.fws.gov/international/wildlife-without-borders/western-hemisphere/ Western Hemisphere], [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service]].</ref><ref>[https://us.fulbrightonline.org/countries/selectedregion/18 Western Hemisphere], [[Fulbright Program]].</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nThe Western Hemisphere consists of the [[Americas]], the western portions of [[Europe]] and [[Africa]], the [[Cape Dezhnev|extreme eastern tip]] of [[Siberia]] ([[Russia]]), numerous territories in [[Oceania]], and a portion of [[Antarctica]], while excluding some of the [[Aleutian Islands]] to the southwest of the [[Alaska|Alaskan]] mainland.\n\nThe center of the Western Hemisphere is located in the [[Pacific Ocean]] at the intersection of the [[90th meridian west]] and the [[Equator]], among the [[Gal\u00e1pagos Islands]]. The nearest land is [[Genovesa Island]] at {{coord|0.316667|N|89.95|W|format=dms|display=inline}}.\n\nThe [[list of highest mountains on Earth|highest mountain]] in the Western Hemisphere is [[Aconcagua]] in the [[Andes]] of [[Argentina]] at {{convert|6960.8|m|ft}}.<ref name=\"UNC-Sigma\">{{cite web|url= http://www.uncu.edu.ar/novedades/index/informe-cientifico-que-estudia-el-aconcagua-el-coloso-de-america-mide-69608-metros|title= Informe cient\u00edfico que estudia el Aconcagua, el Coloso de Am\u00e9rica mide 6960,8 metros|language= Spanish|trans-title= Scientific Report on Aconcagua, the Colossus of America measures 6960,8m|year= 2012|publisher= [[Universidad Nacional de Cuyo]]|accessdate= September 3, 2012|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120908061725/http://www.uncu.edu.ar/novedades/index/informe-cientifico-que-estudia-el-aconcagua-el-coloso-de-america-mide-69608-metros|archivedate= September 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe tallest building or tower in the Western Hemisphere is the CN tower, located in Toronto, Ontario, Canada at {{coord|43|38|33.22|N|79|23|13.41|W|type:landmark|name=CN Tower}}.\n\n===Proposed revision of hemispheric borders===\nIn an attempt to define the Western Hemisphere as the parts of the world which are not part of the [[Old World]], there also exist projections which use the [[20th meridian west]] and the diametrically opposed [[160th meridian east]] to define the hemisphere.<ref name=\":0\">{{citation | last = Olson | first = Judy M | contribution = Projecting the hemisphere | url=https://courseware.e-education.psu.edu/projection/chapter4.html |title=Matching the map projection to the need | editor1-last = Robinson | editor1-first = Arthur H | editor2-last =  Snyder | editor2-first = John P | year = 1997 | place = Bethesda, MD | publisher = Cartography and Geographic Information Society, American Congress on Surveying and Mapping}}.<br>- {{citation | contribution = Western Hemisphere | title =  Merriam-Webster's Geographical Dictionary | edition = 3rd | year = 2001 | place = Springfield, Massachusetts | publisher = Merriam-Webster | page = 1294}}.</ref> This projection excludes the European and African mainlands and a small portion of northeast [[Greenland]], but includes more of eastern Russia and Oceania.\n\n== Sovereign states in both hemispheres ==\n\nBelow is a list of the sovereign states which are in both the Western and Eastern Hemispheres on the [[IERS Reference Meridian]], in order from north to south:\n\n* {{flagdeco|Denmark|size=23px}} [[Denmark]] (due to [[Greenland]] and the [[Faroe Islands]]; mainland Denmark lies entirely in the Eastern Hemisphere).\n* {{flagdeco|Norway|size=23px}} [[Norway]] (due to [[Jan Mayen]]; mainland Norway lies entirely in the Eastern Hemisphere).\n* {{Flagdeco|United Kingdom|size=23px}} [[United Kingdom]], passing through [[Greenwich]], [[London]]. Most of the country is in the Western Hemisphere.\n* {{flagdeco|France|size=23px}} [[France]], passing through [[Puynormand]] ([[Gironde]].) About 1/3 of the country, including cities like [[Nantes]] or [[Bordeaux]], lies in the Western Hemisphere.\n* {{flagdeco|Spain|size=23px}} [[Spain]], passing through [[Castell\u00f3n de la Plana|Castell\u00f3 de la Plana]] ([[Valencian Community]].) Most of Spain, including the capital [[Madrid]], the [[Canary Islands]] and the southern half of its Mediterranean [[territorial waters]], lies in the Western Hemisphere. Spanish, [[Morocco|Moroccan]] and Algerian Mediterranean waters are the only part of the [[Mediterranean Sea]] located in the Western Hemisphere.\n* {{flagdeco|Algeria|size=23px}} [[Algeria]], passing through [[Stidia]]. About 1/4 of the country including [[Oran]], Algeria's second largest city, is in the Western Hemisphere.\n* {{flagdeco|Mali|size=23px}} [[Mali]], passing through the municipal area of [[Gao]]. Most of Mali, including the capital [[Bamako]], lies in the Western Hemisphere.\n* {{flagdeco|Burkina Faso|size=23px}} [[Burkina Faso]], passing through [[Lalgaye Department|Lalgaye]]. Most of the country, including the capital [[Ouagadougou]], is in the Western Hemisphere.\n* {{flagdeco|Ghana|size=23px}} [[Ghana]], passing through [[Tema]]. Most of Ghana, including the capital [[Accra]], lies in the Western Hemisphere.\n* {{flagdeco|Togo|size=23px}} [[Togo]], passing near Tami ([[Savanes Region, Togo|Savanes Region]]).\n\nBelow is a list of the sovereign states which are in both the Western and Eastern Hemispheres along the [[180th meridian]], in order from north to south. With the exception of the United States ([[Wake Island]]), all of them are located on just one side of the [[International Date Line]], which is curved around them.\n\n* {{flagdeco|Russia|size=23px}} [[Russia]] ([[Siberia]], [[Russian Far East|Far East]])\n* {{flagdeco|United States|size=23px}} [[United States]] ([[United States Minor Outlying Islands]], [[Aleutian Islands]], [[Northern Mariana Islands]], [[Guam]])\n* {{flagdeco|Kiribati|size=23px}} [[Kiribati]]\n* {{flagdeco|Tuvalu|size=23px}} [[Tuvalu]]\n* {{flagdeco|Fiji|size=23px}} [[Fiji]]\n* {{flagdeco|New Zealand|size=23px}} [[New Zealand]] ([[Kermadec Islands|Kermadec]] and [[Chatham Islands|Chatham Island]] groups are east of the 180th meridian)\n\nOne sovereign state has territory on both hemispheres, but neither the prime meridian nor the 180th meridian passes through its territory:\n\n* {{flagdeco|Netherlands|size=23px}} [[Kingdom of the Netherlands|Netherlands]] (The islands of the [[Caribbean Netherlands]] lie entirely within the Western Hemisphere while the [[Netherlands|European Netherlands]] lies entirely in the Eastern Hemisphere.)\n\n== Countries and territories in the Western Hemisphere but not in the Americas ==\nThe following countries and territories lie outside the [[Americas]] yet are entirely/mostly or partially within the Western Hemisphere:\n\n{|\n|-\n|valign=top width=33%|\n\n;<big>[[Africa]]</big>\n;<small>Entirely</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Azores|size=23px}} [[Azores]] ([[Portugal]])\n* {{flagdeco|Cape Verde|size=23px}} [[Cape Verde]]\n* {{flagdeco|Gambia|size=23px}} [[Gambia]]\n* {{flagdeco|Guinea|size=23px}} [[Guinea]]\n* {{flagdeco|Guinea-Bissau|size=23px}} [[Guinea-Bissau]]\n* {{flagdeco|Ivory Coast|size=23px}} [[Ivory Coast]]\n* {{flagdeco|Liberia|size=23px}} [[Liberia]]\n* {{flagdeco|Madeira|size=23px}} [[Madeira]] ([[Portugal]])\n* {{flagdeco|Mauritania|size=23px}} [[Mauritania]]\n* {{flagdeco|Morocco|size=23px}} [[Morocco]]\n* {{flagdeco|Saint Helena|size=23px}} [[Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha]] ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flagdeco|Senegal|size=23px}} [[Senegal]]\n* {{flagdeco|Sierra Leone|size=23px}} [[Sierra Leone]]\n* {{flagdeco|Western Sahara|size=23px}} [[Western Sahara]] ([[Political status of Western Sahara|''Disputed'']])\n\n;<small>Mostly</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Burkina Faso|size=23px}} [[Burkina Faso]]\n* {{flagdeco|Ghana|size=23px}} [[Ghana]]\n* {{flagdeco|Mali|size=23px}} [[Mali]]\n\n;<small>Partially</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Algeria|size=23px}} [[Algeria]]\n* {{flagdeco|Togo|size=23px}} [[Togo]]\n\n<br />\n\n;<big>[[Antarctica]]</big> \n;<small>Entirely</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Antarctica|size=23px}} [[Peter I Island]] ([[Antarctic Treaty System|Antarctic Treaty]] signatories / [[Territorial claims in Antarctica|Claimed]] by [[Norway]])\n* {{flagdeco|South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands|size=23px}} [[South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands]] (Administered by the [[United Kingdom]] / Claimed by [[Argentina]]){{dubious|reason = Not part of Antarctica|date=March 2018}}\n* {{flagdeco|Antarctica|size=23px}} [[South Orkney Islands]] ([[Antarctic Treaty System|Antarctic Treaty]] signatories / [[Territorial claims in Antarctica|Claimed]] by the [[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flagdeco|Antarctica|size=23px}} [[South Shetland Islands]] ([[Antarctic Treaty System|Antarctic Treaty]] signatories / [[Territorial claims in Antarctica|Claimed]] by the [[United Kingdom]])\n\n;<small>Partially</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Antarctica|size=23px}} [[Antarctica]] ([[Antarctic Treaty System|Antarctic Treaty]] signatories)\n** {{flagdeco|Antarctica|size=23px}} [[Antarctic Peninsula]] (Entirely){{dubious|reason = Not a territorial entity|date=March 2018}}\n** {{flagdeco|Antarctica|size=23px}} [[East Antarctica]] (Partially){{dubious|reason = Not a territorial entity|date=March 2018}}\n** {{flagdeco|Antarctica|size=23px}} [[West Antarctica]] (Entirely){{dubious|reason = Not a territorial entity|date=March 2018}}\n** {{flagdeco|Antarctica|size=23px}} [[Transantarctic Mountains]] (Entirely){{dubious|reason = Not a territorial entity|date=March 2018}}\n\n|valign=top width=33%|\n\n;<big>[[Asia]]</big>\n;<small>Partially</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Russia|size=23px}} [[Russia]] ([[Siberia]])\n\n<br />\n\n;<big>[[Europe]]</big>\n;<small>Entirely</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Bailiwick of Guernsey|size=23px}} [[Bailiwick of Guernsey]] ([[United Kingdom]])\n** {{flagdeco|Alderney|size=23px}} [[Alderney]]\n** {{flagdeco|Guernsey|size=23px}} [[Guernsey]]\n** {{flagdeco|Sark|size=23px}} [[Sark]]\n* {{flagdeco|Jersey|size=23px}} [[Jersey|Bailiwick of Jersey]] ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flagdeco|Faroe Islands|size=23px}} [[Faroe Islands]] ([[Denmark]])\n* {{flagdeco|Gibraltar|size=23px}} [[Gibraltar]] ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flagdeco|Iceland|size=23px}} [[Iceland]]\n* {{flagdeco|Isle of Man|size=23px}} [[Isle of Man]] ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flagdeco|Jan Mayen|size=23px}} [[Jan Mayen]] ([[Norway]])\n* {{flagdeco|Portugal|size=23px}} [[Portugal]]\n* {{flagdeco|Republic of Ireland|size=23px}} [[Republic of Ireland]]\n* {{flagdeco|United Kingdom|size=23px}} [[Rockall]] ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flagdeco|Shetland|size=23px}} [[Shetland]] ([[United Kingdom]])\n\n;<small>Mostly</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Spain|size=23px}} [[Spain]]\n* {{flagdeco|United Kingdom|size=23px}} [[United Kingdom]]\n** {{flagdeco|England|size=23px}} [[England]] (Mostly)\n** {{flagdeco|United Kingdom|size=23px}} [[Northern Ireland]] (Entirely)\n** {{flagdeco|Scotland|size=23px}} [[Scotland]] (Entirely)\n** {{flagdeco|Wales|size=23px}} [[Wales]] (Entirely)\n\n;<small>Partially</small>\n* {{flagdeco|France|size=23px}} [[France]] ([[Metropolitan France|Metropolitan]])\n\n|valign=top width=33%|\n\n;<big>[[Oceania]]</big>\n;<small>Entirely</small>\n* {{flagdeco|American Samoa|size=23px}} [[American Samoa]] ([[United States]])\n* {{flagdeco|Baker Island|size=23px}} [[Baker Island]] ([[United States]])\n* {{flagdeco|Chatham Islands|size=23px}} [[Chatham Islands]] ([[New Zealand]])\n* {{flagdeco|Clipperton Island|size=23px}} [[Clipperton Island]] ([[France]])\n* {{flagdeco|Cook Islands|size=23px}} [[Cook Islands]] ([[New Zealand]])\n* {{flagdeco|Easter Island|size=23px}} [[Easter Island]] ([[Chile]])\n* {{flagdeco|French Polynesia|size=23px}} [[French Polynesia]] (including [[Tahiti]]) ([[France]])\n* {{flagdeco|Gal\u00e1pagos Islands|size=23px}} [[Gal\u00e1pagos Islands]] ([[Ecuador]])\n* {{flagdeco|Hawaii|size=23px}} [[Hawaii]] ([[United States]])\n* {{flagdeco|Howland Island|size=23px}} [[Howland Island]] ([[United States]])\n* {{flagdeco|Jarvis Island|size=23px}} [[Jarvis Island]] ([[United States]])\n* {{flagdeco|Johnston Atoll|size=23px}} [[Johnston Atoll]] ([[United States]])\n* {{flagdeco|New Zealand|size=23px}} [[Kermadec Islands]] ([[New Zealand]])\n* {{flagdeco|Kingman Reef|size=23px}} [[Kingman Reef]] ([[United States]])\n* {{flagdeco|Midway Atoll|size=23px}} [[Midway Atoll]] ([[United States]])\n* {{flagdeco|Niue|size=23px}} [[Niue]] ([[Realm of New Zealand|New Zealand]])\n* {{flagdeco|Palmyra Atoll|size=23px}} [[Palmyra Atoll]] ([[United States]])\n* {{flagdeco|Pitcairn Islands|size=23px}} [[Pitcairn Islands]] ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flagdeco|Samoa|size=23px}} [[Samoa]]\n* {{flagdeco|Tokelau|size=23px}} [[Tokelau]] ([[New Zealand]])\n* {{flagdeco|Tonga|size=23px}} [[Tonga]]\n\n;<small>Mostly</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Kiribati|size=23px}} [[Kiribati]]\n* {{flagdeco|Wallis and Futuna|size=23px}} [[Wallis and Futuna]] ([[France]])\n\n;<small>Partially</small>\n* {{flagdeco|Fiji|size=23px}} [[Fiji]]\n* {{flagdeco|Tuvalu|size=23px}} [[Tuvalu]]\n\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commonscatinline}}\n\n{{Hemispheres of the Earth}}\n\n[[Category:Western Hemisphere| ]]\n[[Category:Hemispheres of Earth]]\n", "name_user": "172.58.99.114", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_Hemisphere"}
{"title_page": "Kahoot!", "text_new": "{{short description|Online quiz platform}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = Kahoot!\n| logo = Kahoot Logo.svg\n| screenshot = Kahoot iOS screenshot.png\n\n| caption = The Kahoot app running on an iPad\n| url = Main website: {{URL|https://kahoot.com}}<br>Player login: {{URL|https://kahoot.it}}\n| commercial = Yes\n| registration = None for quiz participation; required for quiz creation\n| language =Only English\n| num_users = <!-- provide a reliable source before changing this. -->50 million monthly active users (as of May 2017)<ref name=tech.eu/>\n| owner = Kahoot!\n| launch_date = March 2013<ref name=\":2\"/>\n}}\n\n'''Kahoot!''' is a [[Game based learning|game-based learning]] platform, used as [[educational technology]] in schools and other educational institutions. Its learning games, \"Kahoots\", are user-generated multiple-choice quizzes that can be accessed via a [[web browser]] or the Kahoot app.\n\nKahoot! can be used to review students' knowledge, for [[formative assessment]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://cit.duke.edu/blog/2015/07/kahoot-as-formative-assessment/|title=Kahoot! as Formative Assessment - Center for Instructional Technology|date=2015-07-02|work=Center for Instructional Technology|access-date=2017-08-09|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201123005/https://cit.duke.edu/blog/2015/07/kahoot-as-formative-assessment/|archive-date=2017-02-01|url-status=dead}}</ref> or as a break from traditional classroom activities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tomorrowslearners.com/why-kahoot-is-one-of-my-favourite-classroom-tools/|title=Why Kahoot is one of my favourite classroom tools \u2014 Tomorrow's Learners|access-date=2017-08-09|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810012336/http://tomorrowslearners.com/why-kahoot-is-one-of-my-favourite-classroom-tools/|archive-date=2017-08-10|url-status=live}}</ref> Kahoot! also includes [[trivia]] quizzes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.acpl.lib.in.us/home/explore/teens/notes-from-the-underground/teens/2017/05/22/kahoot-trivia|title=Kahoot Trivia|website=Allen County Public Library|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013507/http://www.acpl.lib.in.us/home/explore/teens/notes-from-the-underground/teens/2017/05/22/kahoot-trivia|archivedate=2017-08-10|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History and development==\nKahoot! was founded in 2013 by Johan Brand, Jamie Brooker and Morten Versvik in a joint project with the [[Norwegian University of Science and Technology]]. They teamed up with Professor Alf Inge Wang and were later joined by Norwegian entrepreneur [[\u00c5smund Furuseth]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Kahoot! was launched in a private beta at SXSWedu in March 2013 and the beta was released to the public in September 2013.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://kahoot.com/company/|title=About Kahoot! {{!}} Company History & Key Facts|work=Kahoot!|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103042411/https://kahoot.com/company/|archive-date=2018-11-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nKahoot! was designed for [[Social learning (social pedagogy)|social learning]], with learners gathered around a common screen such as an [[interactive whiteboard]], projector, or a computer monitor. The site can also be used through [[Videotelephony|screen-sharing]] tools such as [[Skype]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://education.microsoft.com/skypekahoot|title=Skype in the Classroom & Kahoot - Microsoft in Education|website=education.microsoft.com|language=en|access-date=2017-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810012026/https://education.microsoft.com/skypekahoot|archive-date=2017-08-10|url-status=dead}}</ref>, or [[Google Hangouts]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kahoot.uservoice.com/knowledgebase/articles/827223-can-i-play-kahoot-with-others-remotely|title=Can I play Kahoot! with others remotely?|website=Kahoot! Support|language=en|access-date=2018-06-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612142456/https://kahoot.uservoice.com/knowledgebase/articles/827223-can-i-play-kahoot-with-others-remotely|archive-date=2018-06-12|url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[game design]] is such that the players are required to frequently look up from their devices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inclusivedesign.no/ict/kahoot-article172-261.html|title=Kahoot! - Inclusive Design|last=www.corepublish.no|first=CorePublish -|website=www.inclusivedesign.no|language=en|access-date=2017-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013619/http://www.inclusivedesign.no/ict/kahoot-article172-261.html|archive-date=2017-08-10|url-status=live}}</ref> The gameplay is simple; all players connect using a generated game [[Personal identification number|PIN]] shown on the common screen, and use a device to answer questions created by a teacher, business leader, or other person. These questions can be changed to award points. Points then show up on the leaderboard after each question.\n\nKahoot! has now implemented 'Jumble'. Jumble questions challenge players to place answers in the correct order rather than selecting a single correct answer. It offers a new experience that encourages even more focus from players. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kahoot.com/blog/2016/12/13/jumble-is-live/|title=Kahoot Jumble|website=Kahoot|access-date=2019-02-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219015551/https://kahoot.com/blog/2016/12/13/jumble-is-live/|archive-date=2019-02-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nKahoot! can be played through different [[web browser]]s and mobile devices through its web interface.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kahoot.uservoice.com/knowledgebase/articles/498970-is-my-browser-device-suitable-to-host-or-play-a-ka|title=Is my browser/device suitable to host or play a Kahoot? \u2013 Kahoot! Support|website=kahoot.uservoice.com|language=en|access-date=2017-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013254/https://kahoot.uservoice.com/knowledgebase/articles/498970-is-my-browser-device-suitable-to-host-or-play-a-ka|archive-date=2017-08-10|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Kahoot! reached one billion cumulative participating players and in the month of May, the company was reported to have 50 million monthly active unique users.<ref name=\"tech.eu\">{{Cite news|url=http://tech.eu/brief/kahoot-1-billion-players/|title=Norwegian edtech company Kahoot! reaches 1 billion players|work=Tech.eu|access-date=2017-11-01|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107013852/http://tech.eu/brief/kahoot-1-billion-players/|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/amitchowdhry/2017/08/28/how-kahoot-quickly-hit-one-billion-players-while-helping-advance-education/#7367a87f7393|title=How Kahoot! Quickly Hit One Billion Players While Helping Advance Education|last=Chowdhry|first=Amit|work=Forbes|access-date=2017-11-01|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107034510/https://www.forbes.com/sites/amitchowdhry/2017/08/28/how-kahoot-quickly-hit-one-billion-players-while-helping-advance-education/#7367a87f7393|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2017, Kahoot! launched a mobile application for homework.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thejournal.com/articles/2017/09/14/homework-game-changer-kahoot-launches-mobile-app.aspx|title=Homework Game Changer Kahoot! Launches Mobile App -- THE Journal|website=THE Journal|language=en|access-date=2017-10-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013172936/https://thejournal.com/articles/2017/09/14/homework-game-changer-kahoot-launches-mobile-app.aspx|archive-date=2017-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/09/14/kahoot-launches-mobile-app-to-make-homework-fun/|title=Kahoot launches mobile app to make homework fun {{!}} GamesBeat|website=venturebeat.com|date=2017-09-14|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013173526/https://venturebeat.com/2017/09/14/kahoot-launches-mobile-app-to-make-homework-fun/|archive-date=2017-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kahoot in a classroom.jpg|thumb|Kahoot being used in an English lesson in a Thai high school]]\n\nAs of 2017, Kahoot! has raised $26.5 million in funding from Northzone, Creandum and [[Microsoft Ventures]].<ref name=\":0\" /> As of October 11, 2018, Kahoot! is valued at $300 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-10-11-educational-games-startup-kahoot-valued-at-usd300-million|title=Educational games startup Kahoot valued at $300 million|work=GamesIndustry.biz|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108224641/https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-10-11-educational-games-startup-kahoot-valued-at-usd300-million|archive-date=2018-11-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Kahoot Managing Investor Matthew Swanson and Kahoot CEO Daniel Magruder sold a majority of shares to Magruder, along with 2 and 3 percent shares to Colin Worthington and Edgar Cervantes, respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kahoot.com/company/#history|title=Kahoot|last=|first=|date=|website=www.google.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\n== Research and prototypes ==\nThe game concept used in Kahoot! started out as an idea of Professor Alf Inge Wang<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=EObDw_AAAAAJ&hl=en&oi=ao|title=Alf Inge Wang - Google Scholar Citations}}</ref> at Department for Computer Science at the Norwegian University of Science and Technology in 2006, which resulted in multiple prototypes that were developed and tested in experiments conducted in collaboration with master students. The idea was to transform the classroom, where the teacher acted as the game show host and the students were contenders using their own mobile devices. The initial prototype was named Lecture Quiz.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.idi.ntnu.no/~alfw/lecturequiz|title=Lecture Quiz|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228014947/http://www.idi.ntnu.no/~alfw/lecturequiz/|archive-date=2013-12-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Lecture Quiz 1.0 was developed in 2006 before real smartphones were available (first iPhone was released June 29, 2007). The server was implemented in [[Java (programming language)|Java]] and [[MySQL]] integrated with an [[Apache Tomcat|Apache]] Web server, the teacher client has implemented as a [[Java (programming language)|Java]] application in combination with [[OpenGL|Open GL]] for graphics, while the student clients were implemented on [[Java Platform, Micro Edition|Java 2 Micro Edition]], which made it possible to run the client on both mobile phones and laptops.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Alf Inge|last2=\u00d8fsdahl|first2=Terje|last3=M\u00f8rch-Storstein|first3=Ole Kristian|year=2007|title=Lecture quiz-a mobile game concept for lectures|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&as_sdt=1%2C5&q=%22Lecture+quiz-a+mobile+game+concept+for+lectures%22&btnG=|journal=International Conference on Software Engineering and Application|publisher=IASTED|volume=11|pages=305\u2013310|via=Google Scholar}}</ref> Those students who played the game using their own laptops could use the [[Wi-Fi]] available at the university, while those playing using mobile phones had to use [[3G]] over the cellular network. The latter was a disadvantage, as the students had to pay out of their own pocket to play Lecture Quiz as the telecom providers at that time charged per megabyte transferred. The first experiment with Lecture Quiz was carried out in a classroom with twenty students at the Norwegian University of Science and Technology where the focus was on usability and usefulness.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Alf Inge|last2=\u00d8fsdahl|first2=Terje|last3=M\u00f8rch-Storstein|first3=Ole Kristian|year=2008|title=An evaluation of a mobile game concept for lectures|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&as_sdt=1%2C5&q=%22An+evaluation+of+a+mobile+game+concept+for+lectures%22&btnG=|journal=Conference on Software Engineering Education and Training|publisher=IEEE|volume=21|pages=197\u2013204|via=Google Scholar}}</ref> The results from the experiment showed that Lecture Quiz was relatively easy to use, contributed to increased learning, that it was entertaining, and increased the motivation for attending more lectures. From 2006 to 2011, four versions of Lecture Quiz were developed, where the main changes were related to improved usability, making it easier to create quizzes, and using newer technology for implementation.\n\nLecture Quiz 2.0 was the first prototype where both teacher and student clients had web-interfaces. An experiment testing the 2.0 prototype showed that the usability had been improved both for the teacher and the student clients, and that the concept increased students' motivation, engagement, concentration and perceived learning.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wu|first=Bian|last2=Wang|first2=Alf Inge|last3=B\u00f8rresen|first3=Erling Andreas|last4=Tidemann|first4=Knut Andre|year=2011|title=Improvement of a Lecture Game Concept - Implementing Lecture Quiz 2.0.|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/221130592|journal=International Conference on Computer Supported Education|volume=3|pages=26\u201335|via=ResearchGate}}</ref> The last version of Lecture Quiz was version 3.0, with significantly improved user-interface implemented using [[HTML5|HTML 5]] and [[Cascading Style Sheets|CSS3]], avatars, and multiple game/team modes. Lecture Quiz 3.0 was tested internally at the university as well as externally at various schools such as at Skaun Ungdomsskole where the students rejoiced over having a test in social science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nrk.no/viten/dataspel-i-timen-testar-elevane-1.8196102|title=Dataspel i timen testar elevane \u2013 NRK Viten \u2013 Nyheter innen vitenskap og forskning|date=2012-06-15|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426224011/https://www.nrk.no/viten/dataspel-i-timen-testar-elevane-1.8196102|archive-date=2019-04-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince Kahoot! was launched in 2013, the research community has conducted many experiments related to the effects of using the game-based learning platform in classrooms. A quasi-experiment conducted at the Norwegian University of Science and Technology with 252 students participating investigated the wear-out effect of Kahoot! by comparing students' perception of the system after playing once vs. playing frequently over five months.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Alf Inge|year=2015|title=The wear out effect of a game-based student response system|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&as_sdt=1%2C5&q=%22The+wear+out+effect+of+a+game-based+student+response+system%22&btnG=|journal=Computers & Education|publisher=Elsevier|volume=82|pages=217\u2013227|via=Google Scholar|doi=10.1016/j.compedu.2014.11.004|hdl=11250/2496267|hdl-access=free}}</ref> The results did not show any statistically significant reductions in students' engagement, motivation, concentration or perceived learning over time, but there was a significant change in classroom dynamics (less communication among players after five months). The conclusion was that Kahoot! manage to boost students' engagement, motivation, concentration and learning after using it repeatedly for five months. The core factor to keep students' attention after heavy repeated usage was found to be the competitive nature of Kahoot!.\n\nThere is also research that investigates how Kahoot! performs compared to other tools and platforms. In a quasi-experiment with 384 students at the Norwegian University of Science and Technology, Kahoot! was compared to using a paper quiz and a simple polling system called Clicker.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Alf Inge|last2=Zhu|first2=Meng|last3=S\u00e6tre|first3=Rune|year=2016|title=The effect of digitizing and gratifying quizzing in classrooms|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&as_sdt=1,5&q=%22The+Effect+of+Digitizing+and+Gamifying+Quizzing+in+Classrooms%22|journal=European Conference on Games Based Learning|publisher=Academic Conferences and Publishing International|volume=10|pages=729\u2013736|via=Google Scholar}}</ref> The results show statistically significant improvement in motivation, engagement, enjoyment, and concentration for the gamified approach (Kahoot!) compared to the two other. However, the results did not show any significant differences in learning outcomes.\n\nAnother quasi-experiment at the Norwegian University of Science and Technology, in which 593 students participated, investigated how the use of points and audio in Kahoot! affects concentration, engagement, enjoyment, learning, motivation and classroom dynamics.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Alf Inge|last2=Lieberoth|first2=Andreas|year=2016|title=The effect of points and audio on concentration, engagement, enjoyment, learning, motivation, and classroom dynamics using Kahoot!|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&as_sdt=1%2C5&q=%22The+effect+of+points+and+audio+on+concentration%2C+engagement%2C+enjoyment%2C+learning%2C+motivation%2C+and+classroom+dynamics+using+Kahoot%21%22&btnG=|journal=European Conference on Games Based Learning|publisher=Academic Conferences International Limited|volume=10|pages=737\u2013746|via=Google Scholar}}</ref> The results reveal that there are some significant differences whether audio and points are used in the areas of concentration, engagement, enjoyment and motivation. The worst result was for the case where both audio and points were turned off. The most surprising finding was how classroom dynamics was positively affected by the use of audio.\n\nAccording to research by two students at the Norwegian University of Science and Technology, the [[network latency]] in accessing the website greatly influences the [[quality of experience]] of the platform, in both longitudinal and cross-section studies, with a sample size N=21.<ref>{{cite thesis|last1=Underdal|first1=Anlaug G\u00e5rdsrud|last2=Sunde|first2=Marthe Thorine|title=Investigating QoE in a Cloud-Based Classroom Response System|date=5 September 2014|hdl=11250/262998}}</ref> It was found that about 70% of the sample size regard Kahoot! as having positive results on all delay levels, while a varying number of students (between 10-20%) report that the platform is too time-consuming, forming a direct relationship with the duration of the delay.\n\nA [https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0360131520300208 literature review containing 93 studies on the effect of using Kahoot! for learning] was published in the journal [https://www.journals.elsevier.com/computers-and-education Computers & Education] in 2020.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Alf Inge|last2=Tahir|first2=Rabail|year=2020|title=The effect of using Kahoot! for learning \u2013 A literature review|journal=Computers & Education|publisher=Elsevier|volume=149|pages=103818|doi=10.1016/j.compedu.2020.103818|doi-access=free}}</ref> This is the first literature review that investigates most published studies (experiments, case studies, surveys, etc.) on how to use Kahoot! affects learning in the classroom. The focus of the review is on learning performance, classroom dynamics, students' and teachers' attuites and perceptions, and student anxiety. The main conclusion is that Kahoot! has a positive effect on learning performance, classroom dynamics, attuites, and anxiety, and the main challenges include technical problems, see questions and answers, time stress, afraid of losing, and hard to catch up. Studies included in this review use a mixture of quantitative and qualitative methods that reveal among other things that Kahoot! has statistical significant improvement in learning performance compared to traditional teaching and other tools, a statistically significant improvement on students\u2019 and teachers\u2019 perception of lectures, statistically significant improvement in classroom dynamics, and that Kahoot! can reduce students\u2019 anxiety compared to traditional teaching and other tools.\n\n== In popular culture ==\nKahoot!'s growing popularity in schools led to it becoming an [[Internet meme]]. Its interface, as well as catchy music<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hnnUD9-hD8A Kahoot Lobby Music - YouTube<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>, has inspired many memes and social media accounts dedicated to posting such content. The website even has its own [[Know Your Meme]] page.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/subcultures/kahoot|title=Kahoot!|website=knowyourmeme.com|language=en|access-date=18 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419232911/https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/subcultures/kahoot|archive-date=19 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, 2019, an Internet user by the name of \"Max\" created an [[Instagram]] account titled \"worlds.largest.kahoot\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/worlds.largest.kahoot/?hl=en|title=@worlds.largest.kahoot \u2022 Instagram photos and videos}}</ref> with the purpose of breaking the previous record of the world's largest Kahoot! game ever.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.instagram.com/p/BvfGLeujEV_/|title= Instagram post|website= instagram.com|language= en|access-date= 18 April 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190515160406/https://www.instagram.com/p/BvfGLeujEV_/|archive-date= 15 May 2019|url-status= live}}</ref> The game was to be live-streamed on the [[YouTube]] channel Maxed<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC2EkGsVDdBiZPqycc897XDQ |title=Maxed |access-date=2019-04-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419222152/https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC2EkGsVDdBiZPqycc897XDQ |archive-date=2019-04-19 |url-status=live }}</ref> on April 19, 2019, but it was later moved to another channel titled Maxed Hangout.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCyTG2CyJqCpSeLt3sVlAVAQ |title=Maxed Hangout |access-date=2019-04-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419220116/https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCyTG2CyJqCpSeLt3sVlAVAQ |archive-date=2019-04-19 |url-status=live }}</ref> The  live-stream<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CRG_NLo_t2o |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-04-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419221730/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CRG_NLo_t2o |archive-date=2019-04-19 |url-status=live }}</ref> had more than 50,000 viewers, but the game couldn't be played as the Kahoot! servers crashed when the number of players attempting to join exceeded the 2000 player limit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://support.kahoot.com/hc/en-us/articles/115003072287-How-many-players-can-join-a-game-|title=How many players can join a game?|website=Help and Support Center|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419231701/https://support.kahoot.com/hc/en-us/articles/115003072287-How-many-players-can-join-a-game-|archive-date=2019-04-19|url-status=live}}</ref> The organizer of the event stated that he would contact the company and reschedule the game.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.instagram.com/p/BwdF0ReBDhV/|title= Instagram post|website= instagram.com|language= en|access-date= 18 April 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190514120012/https://www.instagram.com/p/BwdF0ReBDhV/|archive-date= 14 May 2019|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://kahoot.com/ Official website]\n[[Category:Educational technology]]\n[[Category:Norwegian educational websites]]\n[[Category:Art games]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2013]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Online quiz platform}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = Kahoot!\n| logo = Kahoot Logo.svg\n| screenshot = Kahoot iOS screenshot.png\n\n| caption = The Kahoot app running on an iPad\n| url = Main website: {{URL|https://kahoot.com}}<br>Player login: {{URL|https://kahoot.it}}\n| commercial = Yes\n| registration = None for quiz participation; required for quiz creation\n| language =Only English\n| num_users = <!-- provide a reliable source before changing this. -->50 million monthly active users (as of May 2017)<ref name=tech.eu/>\n| owner = Kahoot!\n| launch_date = March 2013<ref name=\":2\"/>\n}}\n\n'''Kahoot!''' is a [[Game based learning|game-based learning]] platform, used as [[educational technology]] in schools and other educational institutions. Its learning games, \"Kahoots\", are user-generated multiple-choice quizzes that can be accessed via a [[web browser]] or the Kahoot app.\n\nKahoot! can be used to review students' knowledge, for [[formative assessment]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://cit.duke.edu/blog/2015/07/kahoot-as-formative-assessment/|title=Kahoot! as Formative Assessment - Center for Instructional Technology|date=2015-07-02|work=Center for Instructional Technology|access-date=2017-08-09|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201123005/https://cit.duke.edu/blog/2015/07/kahoot-as-formative-assessment/|archive-date=2017-02-01|url-status=dead}}</ref> or as a break from traditional classroom activities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tomorrowslearners.com/why-kahoot-is-one-of-my-favourite-classroom-tools/|title=Why Kahoot is one of my favourite classroom tools \u2014 Tomorrow's Learners|access-date=2017-08-09|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810012336/http://tomorrowslearners.com/why-kahoot-is-one-of-my-favourite-classroom-tools/|archive-date=2017-08-10|url-status=live}}</ref> Kahoot! also includes [[trivia]] quizzes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.acpl.lib.in.us/home/explore/teens/notes-from-the-underground/teens/2017/05/22/kahoot-trivia|title=Kahoot Trivia|website=Allen County Public Library|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013507/http://www.acpl.lib.in.us/home/explore/teens/notes-from-the-underground/teens/2017/05/22/kahoot-trivia|archivedate=2017-08-10|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History and development==\nKahoot! was founded in 2013 by Johan Brand, Jamie Brooker and Morten Versvik in a joint project with the [[Norwegian University of Science and Technology]]. They teamed up with Professor Alf Inge Wang and were later joined by Norwegian entrepreneur [[\u00c5smund Furuseth]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Kahoot! was launched in a private beta at SXSWedu in March 2013 and the beta was released to the public in September 2013.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://kahoot.com/company/|title=About Kahoot! {{!}} Company History & Key Facts|work=Kahoot!|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103042411/https://kahoot.com/company/|archive-date=2018-11-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nKahoot! was designed for [[Social learning (social pedagogy)|social learning]], with learners gathered around a common screen such as an [[interactive whiteboard]], projector, or a computer monitor. The site can also be used through [[Videotelephony|screen-sharing]] tools such as [[Skype]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://education.microsoft.com/skypekahoot|title=Skype in the Classroom & Kahoot - Microsoft in Education|website=education.microsoft.com|language=en|access-date=2017-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810012026/https://education.microsoft.com/skypekahoot|archive-date=2017-08-10|url-status=dead}}</ref>, or [[Google Hangouts]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kahoot.uservoice.com/knowledgebase/articles/827223-can-i-play-kahoot-with-others-remotely|title=Can I play Kahoot! with others remotely?|website=Kahoot! Support|language=en|access-date=2018-06-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612142456/https://kahoot.uservoice.com/knowledgebase/articles/827223-can-i-play-kahoot-with-others-remotely|archive-date=2018-06-12|url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[game design]] is such that the players are required to frequently look up from their devices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inclusivedesign.no/ict/kahoot-article172-261.html|title=Kahoot! - Inclusive Design|last=www.corepublish.no|first=CorePublish -|website=www.inclusivedesign.no|language=en|access-date=2017-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013619/http://www.inclusivedesign.no/ict/kahoot-article172-261.html|archive-date=2017-08-10|url-status=live}}</ref> The gameplay is simple; all players connect using a generated game [[Personal identification number|PIN]] shown on the common screen, and use a device to answer questions created by a teacher, business leader, or other person. These questions can be changed to award points. Points then show up on the leaderboard after each question.\n\nKahoot! has now implemented 'Jumble'. Jumble questions challenge players to place answers in the correct order rather than selecting a single correct answer. It offers a new experience that encourages even more focus from players. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kahoot.com/blog/2016/12/13/jumble-is-live/|title=Kahoot Jumble|website=Kahoot|access-date=2019-02-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219015551/https://kahoot.com/blog/2016/12/13/jumble-is-live/|archive-date=2019-02-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nKahoot! can be played through different [[web browser]]s and mobile devices through its web interface.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kahoot.uservoice.com/knowledgebase/articles/498970-is-my-browser-device-suitable-to-host-or-play-a-ka|title=Is my browser/device suitable to host or play a Kahoot? \u2013 Kahoot! Support|website=kahoot.uservoice.com|language=en|access-date=2017-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013254/https://kahoot.uservoice.com/knowledgebase/articles/498970-is-my-browser-device-suitable-to-host-or-play-a-ka|archive-date=2017-08-10|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Kahoot! reached one billion cumulative participating players and in the month of May, the company was reported to have 50 million monthly active unique users.<ref name=\"tech.eu\">{{Cite news|url=http://tech.eu/brief/kahoot-1-billion-players/|title=Norwegian edtech company Kahoot! reaches 1 billion players|work=Tech.eu|access-date=2017-11-01|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107013852/http://tech.eu/brief/kahoot-1-billion-players/|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/amitchowdhry/2017/08/28/how-kahoot-quickly-hit-one-billion-players-while-helping-advance-education/#7367a87f7393|title=How Kahoot! Quickly Hit One Billion Players While Helping Advance Education|last=Chowdhry|first=Amit|work=Forbes|access-date=2017-11-01|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107034510/https://www.forbes.com/sites/amitchowdhry/2017/08/28/how-kahoot-quickly-hit-one-billion-players-while-helping-advance-education/#7367a87f7393|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2017, Kahoot! launched a mobile application for homework.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thejournal.com/articles/2017/09/14/homework-game-changer-kahoot-launches-mobile-app.aspx|title=Homework Game Changer Kahoot! Launches Mobile App -- THE Journal|website=THE Journal|language=en|access-date=2017-10-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013172936/https://thejournal.com/articles/2017/09/14/homework-game-changer-kahoot-launches-mobile-app.aspx|archive-date=2017-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/09/14/kahoot-launches-mobile-app-to-make-homework-fun/|title=Kahoot launches mobile app to make homework fun {{!}} GamesBeat|website=venturebeat.com|date=2017-09-14|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013173526/https://venturebeat.com/2017/09/14/kahoot-launches-mobile-app-to-make-homework-fun/|archive-date=2017-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kahoot in a classroom.jpg|thumb|Kahoot being used in an English lesson in a Thai high school]]\n\nAs of 2017, Kahoot! has raised $26.5 million in funding from Northzone, Creandum and [[Microsoft Ventures]].<ref name=\":0\" /> As of October 11, 2018, Kahoot! is valued at $300 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-10-11-educational-games-startup-kahoot-valued-at-usd300-million|title=Educational games startup Kahoot valued at $300 million|work=GamesIndustry.biz|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108224641/https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-10-11-educational-games-startup-kahoot-valued-at-usd300-million|archive-date=2018-11-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Kahoot Managing Investor Matthew Swanson and Kahoot CEO Daniel Magruder sold a majority of shares to Magruder, along with 2 and 3 percent shares to Colin Worthington and Edgar Cervantes, respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kahoot.com/company/#history|title=Kahoot|last=|first=|date=|website=www.google.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\n== Research and prototypes ==\nThe game concept used in Kahoot! started out as an idea of Professor Alf Inge Wang<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=EObDw_AAAAAJ&hl=en&oi=ao|title=Alf Inge Wang - Google Scholar Citations}}</ref> at Department for Computer Science at the Norwegian University of Science and Technology in 2006, which resulted in multiple prototypes that were developed and tested in experiments conducted in collaboration with master students. The idea was to transform the classroom, where the teacher acted as the game show host and the students were contenders using their own mobile devices. The initial prototype was named Lecture Quiz.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.idi.ntnu.no/~alfw/lecturequiz|title=Lecture Quiz|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228014947/http://www.idi.ntnu.no/~alfw/lecturequiz/|archive-date=2013-12-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Lecture Quiz 1.0 was developed in 2006 before real smartphones were available (first iPhone was released June 29, 2007). The server was implemented in [[Java (programming language)|Java]] and [[MySQL]] integrated with an [[Apache Tomcat|Apache]] Web server, the teacher client has implemented as a [[Java (programming language)|Java]] application in combination with [[OpenGL|Open GL]] for graphics, while the student clients were implemented on [[Java Platform, Micro Edition|Java 2 Micro Edition]], which made it possible to run the client on both mobile phones and laptops.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Alf Inge|last2=\u00d8fsdahl|first2=Terje|last3=M\u00f8rch-Storstein|first3=Ole Kristian|year=2007|title=Lecture quiz-a mobile game concept for lectures|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&as_sdt=1%2C5&q=%22Lecture+quiz-a+mobile+game+concept+for+lectures%22&btnG=|journal=International Conference on Software Engineering and Application|publisher=IASTED|volume=11|pages=305\u2013310|via=Google Scholar}}</ref> Those students who played the game using their own laptops could use the [[Wi-Fi]] available at the university, while those playing using mobile phones had to use [[3G]] over the cellular network. The latter was a disadvantage, as the students had to pay out of their own pocket to play Lecture Quiz as the telecom providers at that time charged per megabyte transferred. The first experiment with Lecture Quiz was carried out in a classroom with twenty students at the Norwegian University of Science and Technology where the focus was on usability and usefulness.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Alf Inge|last2=\u00d8fsdahl|first2=Terje|last3=M\u00f8rch-Storstein|first3=Ole Kristian|year=2008|title=An evaluation of a mobile game concept for lectures|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&as_sdt=1%2C5&q=%22An+evaluation+of+a+mobile+game+concept+for+lectures%22&btnG=|journal=Conference on Software Engineering Education and Training|publisher=IEEE|volume=21|pages=197\u2013204|via=Google Scholar}}</ref> The results from the experiment showed that Lecture Quiz was relatively easy to use, contributed to increased learning, that it was entertaining, and increased the motivation for attending more lectures. From 2006 to 2011, four versions of Lecture Quiz were developed, where the main changes were related to improved usability, making it easier to create quizzes, and using newer technology for implementation.\n\nLecture Quiz 2.0 was the first prototype where both teacher and student clients had web-interfaces. An experiment testing the 2.0 prototype showed that the usability had been improved both for the teacher and the student clients, and that the concept increased students' motivation, engagement, concentration and perceived learning.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wu|first=Bian|last2=Wang|first2=Alf Inge|last3=B\u00f8rresen|first3=Erling Andreas|last4=Tidemann|first4=Knut Andre|year=2011|title=Improvement of a Lecture Game Concept - Implementing Lecture Quiz 2.0.|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/221130592|journal=International Conference on Computer Supported Education|volume=3|pages=26\u201335|via=ResearchGate}}</ref> The last version of Lecture Quiz was version 3.0, with significantly improved user-interface implemented using [[HTML5|HTML 5]] and [[Cascading Style Sheets|CSS3]], avatars, and multiple game/team modes. Lecture Quiz 3.0 was tested internally at the university as well as externally at various schools such as at Skaun Ungdomsskole where the students rejoiced over having a test in social science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nrk.no/viten/dataspel-i-timen-testar-elevane-1.8196102|title=Dataspel i timen testar elevane \u2013 NRK Viten \u2013 Nyheter innen vitenskap og forskning|date=2012-06-15|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426224011/https://www.nrk.no/viten/dataspel-i-timen-testar-elevane-1.8196102|archive-date=2019-04-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince Kahoot! was launched in 2013, the research community has conducted many experiments related to the effects of using the game-based learning platform in classrooms. A quasi-experiment conducted at the Norwegian University of Science and Technology with 252 students participating investigated the wear-out effect of Kahoot! by comparing students' perception of the system after playing once vs. playing frequently over five months.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Alf Inge|year=2015|title=The wear out effect of a game-based student response system|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&as_sdt=1%2C5&q=%22The+wear+out+effect+of+a+game-based+student+response+system%22&btnG=|journal=Computers & Education|publisher=Elsevier|volume=82|pages=217\u2013227|via=Google Scholar|doi=10.1016/j.compedu.2014.11.004|hdl=11250/2496267|hdl-access=free}}</ref> The results did not show any statistically significant reductions in students' engagement, motivation, concentration or perceived learning over time, but there was a significant change in classroom dynamics (less communication among players after five months). The conclusion was that Kahoot! manage to boost students' engagement, motivation, concentration and learning after using it repeatedly for five months. The core factor to keep students' attention after heavy repeated usage was found to be the competitive nature of Kahoot!.\n\nThere is also research that investigates how Kahoot! perform compared to other tools and platforms. In a quasi-experiment with 384 students at the Norwegian University of Science and Technology, Kahoot! was compared to using a paper quiz and a simple polling system called Clicker.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Alf Inge|last2=Zhu|first2=Meng|last3=S\u00e6tre|first3=Rune|year=2016|title=The effect of digitizing and gratifying quizzing in classrooms|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&as_sdt=1,5&q=%22The+Effect+of+Digitizing+and+Gamifying+Quizzing+in+Classrooms%22|journal=European Conference on Games Based Learning|publisher=Academic Conferences and Publishing International|volume=10|pages=729\u2013736|via=Google Scholar}}</ref> The results show statistically significant improvement in motivation, engagement, enjoyment, and concentration for the gamified approach (Kahoot!) compared to the two other. However, the results did not show any significant differences in learning outcomes.\n\nAnother quasi-experiment at the Norwegian University of Science and Technology, in which 593 students participated, investigated how the use of points and audio in Kahoot! affects concentration, engagement, enjoyment, learning, motivation and classroom dynamics.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Alf Inge|last2=Lieberoth|first2=Andreas|year=2016|title=The effect of points and audio on concentration, engagement, enjoyment, learning, motivation, and classroom dynamics using Kahoot!|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&as_sdt=1%2C5&q=%22The+effect+of+points+and+audio+on+concentration%2C+engagement%2C+enjoyment%2C+learning%2C+motivation%2C+and+classroom+dynamics+using+Kahoot%21%22&btnG=|journal=European Conference on Games Based Learning|publisher=Academic Conferences International Limited|volume=10|pages=737\u2013746|via=Google Scholar}}</ref> The results reveal that there are some significant differences whether audio and points are used in the areas of concentration, engagement, enjoyment and motivation. The worst result was for the case where both audio and points were turned off. The most surprising finding was how classroom dynamics was positively affected by the use of audio.\n\nAccording to research by two students at the Norwegian University of Science and Technology, the [[network latency]] in accessing the website greatly influences the [[quality of experience]] of the platform, in both longitudinal and cross-section studies, with a sample size N=21.<ref>{{cite thesis|last1=Underdal|first1=Anlaug G\u00e5rdsrud|last2=Sunde|first2=Marthe Thorine|title=Investigating QoE in a Cloud-Based Classroom Response System|date=5 September 2014|hdl=11250/262998}}</ref> It was found that about 70% of the sample size regard Kahoot! as having positive results on all delay levels, while a varying number of students (between 10-20%) report that the platform is too time-consuming, forming a direct relationship with the duration of the delay.\n\nA [https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0360131520300208 literature review containing 93 studies on the effect of using Kahoot! for learning] was published in the journal [https://www.journals.elsevier.com/computers-and-education Computers & Education] in 2020.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Alf Inge|last2=Tahir|first2=Rabail|year=2020|title=The effect of using Kahoot! for learning \u2013 A literature review|journal=Computers & Education|publisher=Elsevier|volume=149|pages=103818|doi=10.1016/j.compedu.2020.103818|doi-access=free}}</ref> This is the first literature review that investigates most published studies (experiments, case studies, surveys, etc.) on how to use Kahoot! affects learning in the classroom. The focus of the review is on learning performance, classroom dynamics, students' and teachers' attuites and perceptions, and student anxiety. The main conclusion is that Kahoot! has a positive effect on learning performance, classroom dynamics, attuites, and anxiety, and the main challenges include technical problems, see questions and answers, time stress, afraid of losing, and hard to catch up. Studies included in this review use a mixture of quantitative and qualitative methods that reveal among other things that Kahoot! has statistical significant improvement in learning performance compared to traditional teaching and other tools, a statistically significant improvement on students\u2019 and teachers\u2019 perception of lectures, statistically significant improvement in classroom dynamics, and that Kahoot! can reduce students\u2019 anxiety compared to traditional teaching and other tools.\n\n== In popular culture ==\nKahoot!'s growing popularity in schools led to it becoming an [[Internet meme]]. Its interface, as well as catchy music<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hnnUD9-hD8A Kahoot Lobby Music - YouTube<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>, has inspired many memes and social media accounts dedicated to posting such content. The website even has its own [[Know Your Meme]] page.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/subcultures/kahoot|title=Kahoot!|website=knowyourmeme.com|language=en|access-date=18 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419232911/https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/subcultures/kahoot|archive-date=19 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, 2019, an Internet user by the name of \"Max\" created an [[Instagram]] account titled \"worlds.largest.kahoot\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/worlds.largest.kahoot/?hl=en|title=@worlds.largest.kahoot \u2022 Instagram photos and videos}}</ref> with the purpose of breaking the previous record of the world's largest Kahoot! game ever.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.instagram.com/p/BvfGLeujEV_/|title= Instagram post|website= instagram.com|language= en|access-date= 18 April 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190515160406/https://www.instagram.com/p/BvfGLeujEV_/|archive-date= 15 May 2019|url-status= live}}</ref> The game was to be live-streamed on the [[YouTube]] channel Maxed<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC2EkGsVDdBiZPqycc897XDQ |title=Maxed |access-date=2019-04-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419222152/https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC2EkGsVDdBiZPqycc897XDQ |archive-date=2019-04-19 |url-status=live }}</ref> on April 19, 2019, but it was later moved to another channel titled Maxed Hangout.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCyTG2CyJqCpSeLt3sVlAVAQ |title=Maxed Hangout |access-date=2019-04-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419220116/https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCyTG2CyJqCpSeLt3sVlAVAQ |archive-date=2019-04-19 |url-status=live }}</ref> The  live-stream<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CRG_NLo_t2o |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-04-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419221730/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CRG_NLo_t2o |archive-date=2019-04-19 |url-status=live }}</ref> had more than 50,000 viewers, but the game couldn't be played as the Kahoot! servers crashed when the number of players attempting to join exceeded the 2000 player limit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://support.kahoot.com/hc/en-us/articles/115003072287-How-many-players-can-join-a-game-|title=How many players can join a game?|website=Help and Support Center|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419231701/https://support.kahoot.com/hc/en-us/articles/115003072287-How-many-players-can-join-a-game-|archive-date=2019-04-19|url-status=live}}</ref> The organizer of the event stated that he would contact the company and reschedule the game.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.instagram.com/p/BwdF0ReBDhV/|title= Instagram post|website= instagram.com|language= en|access-date= 18 April 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190514120012/https://www.instagram.com/p/BwdF0ReBDhV/|archive-date= 14 May 2019|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://kahoot.com/ Official website]\n[[Category:Educational technology]]\n[[Category:Norwegian educational websites]]\n[[Category:Art games]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2013]]\n", "name_user": "Usufruct99", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kahoot!"}
{"title_page": "Yasumitsu Sat\u014d", "text_new": "{{Infobox shogi professional\n| name             = Yasumitsu Sat\u014d\n| image            =File:SHOGI Proffesional Yasumitsu Satoh.jpg\n| caption          = Sat\u014d at an October 2015 event.\n| born             = {{birth date and age | 1969 | 10 | 01 | mf=yes}} \n| hometown         = [[Yawata, Kyoto]]\n| nationality      = [[Japanese people|Japanese]]\n| pro_date         = {{event date and age | 1987 | 3 | 25 | 1969 | 10 | 01}}\n| badge_no         = 182\n| teacher          = {{ill | Kaish\u016b Tanaka|ja| \u7530\u4e2d\u9b41\u79c0}} \n| lifetime_titles  = [[Kisei (shogi)#Lifetime Kisei|Lifetime Kisei]]\n| rank             = 9 [[dan (rank)#Modern usage in shogi|dan]]\n| no_titles        = 13\n| tournaments      = 12\n| meijinclass      = A\n| ryuoclass        = 1\n| jsa              = 182\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Yasumitsu Sat\u014d'''|\u4f50\u85e4 \u5eb7\u5149|Sat\u014d Yasumitsu | born October 1, 1969}} is a Japanese [[professional shogi player]] from [[Yawata, Kyoto|Yawata City]] in [[Kyoto Prefecture]], [[Japan]]. He is currently the president of the [[Japan Shogi Association]]. He became a professional in 1987 and is ranked 9-[[Dan (rank)#Modern usage in shogi|dan]]. He has won 13 major titles, is a former [[Meijin]] title holder, and has qualified for the [[Kisei (shogi)#Lifetime Kisei|Lifetime Kisei]] title.\n\n==Early life==\nSat\u014d was born in [[Yawata, Kyoto|Yawata City]] in [[Kyoto Prefecture]] on October 1, 1969.<ref name=\"JSA Database\">{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/player/pro/182.html|script-title=ja:\u68cb\u58eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9: \u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149|title=Kishi D\u0113tab\u0113su: Sat\u014d Yasumitsu|language=ja|trans-title=Professional Shogi Player Database: Yasumitsu Sat\u014d|publisher=[[Japan Shogi Association]]|access-date=October 4, 2017}}</ref> He finished third in the 6th {{ill|Elementary Student Meijin Tournament|ja|\u5c0f\u5b66\u751f\u5c06\u68cb\u540d\u4eba\u6226}} in 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://joshi-shogi.com/event/10th_aomori.html#more|script-title=ja:\u7b2c10\u56de\u8a18\u5ff5\u9752\u68ee\u770c\u5c06\u68cb\u307e\u3064\u308a|title=Dai Jikkai Kinen Aomori-ken Sh\u014dgi Matsuri|language=ja|trans-title=10th Aomori Prefecture Shogi Festival|date=September 21, 2008|publisher=Ladies Shogi Professional-players Association|quote=\u5199\u771f\u30ad\u30e3\u30d7\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3: 1981\u5e74\u306e\u5c0f\u5b66\u751f\u540d\u4eba\u6226, \u4f50\u85e4\u68cb\u738b\u306f3\u4f4d, \u6e96\u512a\u52dd\u306f\u4e2d\u4e95\u73fe\u5973\u6d41\u516d\u6bb5\u3068\u3044\u3046\u8a71\u984c\u306b [Photo caption: The converstation turned to the 1981 Elementary Student Meijin Tournament where Sat\u014d Ki\u014d finished third and Nakai Female Professional 6d finished second]|access-date=November 8, 2017}}</ref> His experience in the tournament led him to want become a shogi professional, and he entered the [[Japan Shogi Association#Headquarters and other offices|Kansai branch]] of the Japan Shogi Association's [[Professional shogi player#Apprenticeship|apprentice school]] at the rank of 6-[[Dan (rank)#Modern usage in shogi|ky\u016b]] in December 1982 as a [[protegee]] of shogi professional {{ill|Kaish\u016b Tanaka|ja|\u7530\u4e2d\u9b41\u79c0}} in December 1982.<ref name=\"2016databook\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NoIRCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA56|script-title=ja:\u73fe\u5f79\u30d7\u30ed\u68cb\u58eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d6\u30c3\u30af2016 [\u4e0a] \u3042-\u305f|title=Geneki Pur\u014d Kishi D\u0113taBukku 2016 [J\u014d] A-Ta Gy\u014d|language=ja|trans-title=2016 Active Shogi Professional Databook [First volume] Letter \"A\" to Letter \"Ta\"|page=56|year=2015|publisher=MyNabi Publishing/Japan Shogi Association|via=[[Google Books]]|access-date=November 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Shogi professional==\nSat\u014d's first appearance a major title match was in 1990 as the challenger to [[K\u014dji Tanigawa]] for the [[\u014ci (shogi)|31st \u014ci title]], but he lost the match 4 games to 3.<ref name=\"2016databook\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/oui/#aswift_0_anchor|script-title=ja:\u738b\u4f4d\u6226: \u904e\u53bb\u306e\u7d50\u679c|title=\u014cisen: Kako no Kekka|language=ja|trans-title=\u014ci tournament: Past results|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref> That same year, he won his first tournament as a professional when he defeated [[Toshiyuki Moriuchi]] to win the {{ill|9th Hayazashi Shinei Tournament|ja|\u65e9\u6307\u3057\u5c06\u68cb\u9078\u624b\u6a29#\u65e9\u6307\u3057\u65b0\u92ed\u6226}}, a [[Rapid chess|quick-play type]] tournament for young players under the age of thirty. He repeated as champion the following year when he won the 10th Hayazashi Shinei Tournament when he defeated [[Taku Morishita]] in the final.<ref name=\"2016databook\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/finished/12/|script-title=ja:\u65e9\u6307\u3057\u5c06\u68cb\u9078\u624b\u6a29\u6226\uff65\u65e9\u6307\u3057\u65b0\u92ed\u6226|title=Hayazahi Sh\u014dgi Senshukensen\uff65Hayazashi Shineisen|language=ja|trans-title=Quick-play Shogi Tournament\uff65Quick-play Young Professional Tournament|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/finished/12/rekidai.html|script-title=ja:\u65e9\u6307\u3057\u5c06\u68cb\u9078\u624b\u6a29\u6226\uff65\u65e9\u6307\u3057\u65b0\u92ed\u6226: \u6b74\u4ee3\u512a\u52dd\u8005\u4e00\u89a7|title=Hayazahi Sh\u014dgi Senshukensen\uff65Hayazashi Shineisen: Rekidai Y\u016bsh\u014dsha Ichiran|language=ja|trans-title=Quick-play Shogi Tournament\uff65Quick-play Young Professional Tournament: Winners list|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Sat\u014d challenged [[Yoshiharu Habu]] for the [[Ry\u016b\u014d|6th Ry\u016b\u014d title]] and won the match 4 games to 2 for his first major title. The same two players met in the title matches for the 7th Ry\u016b\u014d (1994) and 8th Ry\u016b\u014d (1995). Challenger Habu was able to recapture his title by the score of 4 games to 2 in 1994 and then defend it by the same score in 1995.<ref name=\"2016databook\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/ryuuou|script-title=ja:\u7adc\u738b\u6226: \u904e\u53bb\u306e\u7d50\u679c|title=Ry\u016b\u014dsen: Kako no Kekka|language=ja|trans-title=Ry\u016b\u014d tournament: Past results|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Sat\u014d challenged Habu for the [[:\u014ci (shogi)|38th \u014ci title]] Habu, but lost the match by the score of 4 games to 1.<ref name=\"Oi\">{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/oui|script-title=ja:\u738b\u4f4d\u6226: \u904e\u53bb\u306e\u7d50\u679c|title=\u014cisen: Kako no Kekka|language=ja|trans-title=\u014ci tournament: Past results|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 6, 2017}}</ref> The two met once again the following year for the 39th \u014ci title, but Habu defended his title by the score 4 games to 2.<ref name=\"Oi\" /> That same year, Sat\u014d was the challenger to Habu for the [[Ki\u014d|24th Ki\u014d title]], but lost the match 3 games to 0.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/kiou/|script-title=ja:\u68cb\u738b\u6226: \u904e\u53bb\u306e\u7d50\u679c|title=Ki\u014d: Kako no Kekka|language=ja|trans-title=Ki\u014d tournament: Past results|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 6, 2017}}</ref> Sat\u014d once again challenged Habu for the Ki\u014d title in 2001. Sat\u014d won the first game of the 27th Ki\u014d match, but Habu then won the next three games to defend his title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/kiou/27hon/index.html|script-title=ja:\u7b2c27\u671f\u68cb\u738b\u6226 \u6311\u6226\u8005\u6c7a\u5b9a\u30c8\u30fc\u30ca\u30e1\u30f3\u30c8 / \u4e94\u756a\u52dd\u8ca0|title=Dai Nij\u016bnanaki Ki\u014dsen Ch\u014dsensha Kettei T\u014dnamento/Goban Sh\u014dbu|language=ja|trans-title=27th Ki\u014d Tournament: Challenger Tournament/5-game Match|year=2001|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn just his second year in [[Meijin (shogi)#Qualifying|Meijin Class A]], Sat\u014d earned the right to challenge Tanigawa for the [[Meijin (shogi)|56th Meijin title]] (1998) by defeating Habu in a one-game playoff after both players finished league play with a record of 6 wins and 3 losses.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RyaABAAAQBAJ&pg=614|script-title=ja:\u5c06\u68cb\u9806\u4f4d\u622630\u5e74\u53f2 1984-1997\u5e74\u7de8|title=Sh\u014dgi Jun'isen Sanj\u016bnenshi 1984-1997nenhen|language=ja|trans-title=30 Year History of Meijin League Play: Years 1984-1997|year=2014|page=614|publisher=MyNabi Publishing/Japan Shogi Association|isbn=978-4-8399-5306-5|via=[[Google Books]]|access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref> Sat\u014d then proceeded to defeat Tanigawa 4 games to 3 to win the Meijin title for the first time. The following year, Sat\u014d and Tanigawa met again for the 57th Meijin title (1999), with Sat\u014d defending his title by the score of 4 games to 3. Sat\u014d, however, was unable to successfully defend his title for the third consecutive year when he lost to [[Tadahisa Maruyama]] 4 games to 3 in the 58th Meijin title match (200).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/junni/#jo_tab|script-title=ja:\u540d\u4eba\u6226\uff65\u9806\u4f4d\u6226: \u904e\u53bb\u306e\u7d50\u679c|title=Meijinsen\uff65Jun'isen: Kako no Kekka|language=ja|trans-title=Meijin Match\uff65Meijin League Play: Past results|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSat\u014d was the challenger in the 47th \u014csh\u014d (1997) and 49th \u014csh\u014d (1999) title matches against Habu, but lost by the scores of 4 games to 1 and 4 games to 0, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/oushou|script-title=ja:\u738b\u5c06\u6226: \u904e\u53bb\u306e\u7d50\u679c|title=\u014csh\u014dsen: Kako no Kekka|language=ja|trans-title=\u014csh\u014d Tournament: Past results|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref> In 2002, Sat\u014d finished the 51st \u014csh\u014d challenger league play undefeated with six wins to once again challenge to Habu for the title. Sato won the first two games of the match and then split the next four to win the match 4 games to 2,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/oushou/51/hon.html|script-title=ja:\u7b2c51\u671f\u738b\u5c06\u6226 \u4e03\u756a\u52dd\u8ca0\uff65\u6311\u6226\u8005\u6c7a\u5b9a\u30ea\u30fc\u30b0\u6226|title=Dai Goj\u016bikki \u014csh\u014dsen\uff65Nanaban Sh\u014dbu\uff65Ch\u014dsensha Kettei R\u012bgusen|language=ja|trans-title=51st \u014csh\u014d 7-game Match\uff65Challenger League Play|year=2001|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line-->|url=http://www.shikoku-np.co.jp/national/life_topic/20020312000443|script-title=ja:\u4f50\u85e4\u304c\u7fbd\u751f\u304b\u3089\u738b\u5c06\u4f4d\u596a\u53d6 / \u5c06\u68cb\u306e\u738b\u5c06\u6226\u7b2c6\u5c40|title=Sat\u014d ga Habu kara  \u014csh\u014di Dasshu / Sh\u014dgi no \u014csh\u014dsen Dai Rokkyoku|language=ja|trans-title=Sat\u014d takes \u014csh\u014d title from Habu / Shogi \u014csh\u014d match Game 6|date=March 12, 2002|newspaper=[[List of newspapers in Japan#Prefecture papers of Shikoku|Shikoku Shimbun]]|access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref> thus ending his title match losing streak to Habu at eight.<ref name=\"2016databook\" /> The following year, however, Habu was successful in retaking the title from Sat\u014d, winning the 52nd \u014csh\u014d match 4 games to 0.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/oushou/52/hon.html|script-title=ja:\u7b2c52\u671f\u738b\u5c06\u6226 \u4e03\u756a\u52dd\u8ca0\uff65\u6311\u6226\u8005\u6c7a\u5b9a\u30ea\u30fc\u30b0\u6226|title=Dai Goj\u016bniki \u014csh\u014dsen\uff65Nanaban Sh\u014dbu\uff65Ch\u014dsensha Kettei R\u012bgusen|language=ja|trans-title=52nd \u014csh\u014d 7-game Match\uff65Challenger League Play|year=2002|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref> Sat\u014d and Habu met again in 55th \u014csh\u014d (2006) and 56th \u014csh\u014d (2007) title matches with Habu defending his title each time by the score of 4 games to 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.igoshogi.net/topics/detail.php?ID=421|script-title=ja:\u7b2c55\u671f\u738b\u5c06\u6226...\u7fbd\u751f\u738b\u5c06, \u9632\u885b|title=Dai Goj\u016bgoki \u014csh\u014d ... Habu \u014csh\u014d, B\u014dei|language=ja|trans-title=55th \u014csh\u014d Match ... Habu \u014cish\u014d defends title|date=March 23, 2006|publisher=Igo & Shogi Channel|access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.igoshogi.net/topics/detail.php?ID=524|script-title=ja:\u7b2c56\u671f\u738b\u5c06\u6226...\u7fbd\u751f\u738b\u5c06\u306e\u9632\u885b|title=Dai Goj\u016bgoki \u014csh\u014d ... Habu \u014csh\u014d no B\u014dei|language=ja|trans-title=56th \u014csh\u014d Match ... Habu \u014cish\u014d defends title|date=March 22, 2007|publisher=Igo & Shogi Channel|access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Sat\u014d defeated [[Toshiyuki Moriuchi]] (the reigning [[Meijin (shogi)|Meijin]] at the time) to win the [[NHK Cup (shogi)|56th NHK Cup Shogi TV tournament]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.igoshogi.net/topics/detail.php?ID=522&is=1|script-title=ja:\u7b2c56\u56deNHK\u676f\u5c06\u68cb\uff34...\u85e4\u68cb\u8056\u306e\u512a\u52dd|title=Dai Goj\u016brokkai NHKhai Sh\u014dgi T ... Sat\u014d Kisei no Y\u016bsh\u014d|language=ja|trans-title=Sato Kisei Wins 56th NHK Cup|date=March 19, 2007|publisher=Igo & Shogi Channel|access-date=November 7, 2017}}</ref> He defeated [[Daisuke Suzuki (shogi)|Daisuke Suzuki]] the following year to defend his title and become just the third player ever to win the tournament in consecutive years, with the championship game between the two being the first NHK shogi tournament game ever to be [[Live television|broadcast live on TV]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AYbrCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA372|script-title=ja:\u5c06\u68cb\u30bf\u30a4\u30c8\u30eb\u622630\u5e74\u53f2 1998\uff5e2013\u5e74\u7de8|title=Sh\u014dgi Taitorusen Sanj\u016bnenshi 1998-2013nenhen|language=ja|trans-title=30 Year History of Shogi Major Title Matches: Years 1998-2013|year=2014|publisher=MyNabi Publishing/Japan Shogi Association|page=372|isbn=978-4-8399-5097-2|via=Google Books|access-date=November 7, 2017}}</ref> Sat\u014d won the tournament for a third time in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line-->|url=http://www.asahi.com/articles/DA3S12868596.html|script-title=ja:\u4f50\u85e4\u4e5d\u6bb5\u304c\u512a\u52dd \u5c06\u68cb\uff65NHK\u676f|title=Sat\u014d Kudan ga Y\u016bsh\u014d, Shogi\uff65NHKhai|language=ja|trans-title=Sato 9d Wins Shogi NHK Cup|date=March 30, 2017|newspaper=[[Asahi Shimbun]]|access-date=November 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSat\u014d became the ninth professional player to record 1000 victories in official games when he defeated [[Akihito Hirose]] in a Meijin Class A game on July 28, 2017. Sat\u014d is the first player to accomplish such a feat since Habu did so in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/news/2017/07/1000_3.html|script-title=ja:\u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149\u4e5d\u6bb5, 1000\u52dd\uff08\u7279\u5225\u5c06\u68cb\u6804\u8a89\u8cde\uff09\u3092\u9054\u6210\uff01|title=Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Kudan, Sensh\u014d (Tokubetsu Sh\u014dgi Eiyosh\u014d) wo Tassei!|language=ja|trans-title=Yasumitsu Sat\u014d Wins 1000 Official Game (Special Shogi Award)|date=July 29, 2017|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=November 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Yamamura|first=Hideki|url=https://mainichi.jp/articles/20170729/k00/00m/040/157000c|script-title=ja:\u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149\u4e5d\u6bb5\u304c1000\u52dd\u9054\u6210, \u53f2\u4e0a9\u4eba\u76ee|title=Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Kudan ga Sensh\u014d Tassei, Shij\u014d Ky\u016bninme|language=ja|trans-title=Yasumitsu Sato 9d Becomes 9th Player to Reach 1000 Wins|date=July 29, 2017|newspaper=[[Mainichi Shimbun]]|access-date=November 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Playing style ==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=August 2018}}\nHe was known to use a lot of [[j\u014dseki]] positions as a young player, but since 2005 he has often opted for choosing to play creatively with the standard strategies. His new move [[Cheerful Central Rook#5. P-96|5. P-96]] for [[Cheerful Central Rook]] has been widely adopted by many professional players. From a young age he has been known for the depth of his reading, which is called  his \"minute\" or \"meticulous\" style, and of which is said that he can \"read a billion of three-move series in a second\".\n\n==JSA president==\nSat\u014d served as the chairman of the {{ill|Shogi Professional Players' Association|ja|\u65e5\u672c\u5c06\u68cb\u9023\u76df#\u68cb\u58eb\u4f1a}} from April 2011 until January 2017.<ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line-->|url=https://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXLASFG06H8D_W7A200C1000000/|script-title=ja:\u5c06\u68cb\u9023\u76df, \u65b0\u4f1a\u9577\u306b\u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149\u4e5d\u6bb5 \uff62\u4fe1\u983c\u56de\u5fa9\u306b\u5168\u529b\uff63 |title=Sh\u014dgi Renmai, Shinkaicho ni Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Kudan \"Shinrai Kaifuku ni Zenryoku\"|language=ja|trans-title=Japan Shogi Association selects Yasumitsu Sat\u014d 9d as new president. Promises to \"use all his power to restore JSA reputation\"|date=February 6, 2017|newspaper=[[The Nikkei]]|quote=2011\u5e74\u304b\u3089\u68cb\u58eb\u4f1a\u4f1a\u9577\u3092\u52d9\u3081\u3066\u3044\u305f. [Served as chairman of Shogi Professional Players' Association since 2011]|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/news/2017/02/post_1508.html|script-title=ja:\u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149\u68cb\u58eb\u4f1a\u4f1a\u9577\u306e\u8f9e\u4efb\u306b\u95a2\u3059\u308b\u304a\u77e5\u3089\u305b|title=Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Kishikai Kaicho no Jinin ni Kansuru Oshirase|language=ja|trans-title=Announcement regarding Shogi Professional Players' Association Chairman Yasumitsu Sat\u014d's resignation|date=February 1, 2017|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref> He announced his candidacy for the [[Japan Shogi Association#General meetings and the board of directors|JSA's board of directors]] on January 19, 2017, a day after [[K\u014dji Tanigawa]] announced his resignation as JSA president to accept responsibility for the [[Ry\u016b\u014d#29th Ry\u016b\u014d challenger controversy|29th Ry\u016b\u014d challenger controversy]].<ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line-->|url=http://www.asahi.com/articles/DA3S12755945.html|script-title=ja:\u5c06\u68cb\u9023\u76df\u7406\u4e8b\u9078, \u4f50\u85e4\u4e5d\u6bb5\u51fa\u99ac\u3078|title=Sh\u014dgi Renmei Rijisen, Sat\u014d Kudan Sh\u016btsuba e|language=ja|trans-title=Sato 9d Announces Candidacy for JSA Board of Directors|date=January 20, 2017|newspaper=Asahi Shimbun|url-access=subscription|access-date=November 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Yamamura|first1=Hideki|last2=Mogami|first2=Satoshi|url=http://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20170118/p2a/00m/0na/013000c|title=Head of shogi association resigns after top player cleared of cheating|date=January 18, 2017|newspaper=Mainichi Shimbun|access-date=November 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSat\u014d was elected to the JSA's Board of Directors at an emergency meeting of the organization's members on February 6, 2017, and was later chosen by the board at a meeting held the same day to serve out the remainder of Tanigawa's term as JSA president.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/news/2017/02/post_1510.html|script-title=ja:\u65e5\u672c\u5c06\u68cb\u9023\u76df\u65b0\u5f79\u54e1\u306e\u304a\u77e5\u3089\u305b|title=Nihon Sh\u014dgi Renmei Shiyakuin no Oshirase|language=ja|trans-title=Announcement of New Japan Shogi Association Board Members|date=February 6, 2017|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=November 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"JT\">{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer; No by-line-->|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2017/02/07/national/elite-player-tapped-new-shogi-body-chief-defamation-scandal/|title=Elite player tapped as new 'shogi' body chief after defamation scandal|date=February 7, 2017|newspaper=[[The Japan Times]]|agency=[[Kyodo News]]|access-date=October 4, 2017}}</ref> He was re-elected as president for a full two-year term at the [[Japan Shogi Association#General meetings and the board of directors|JSA's general meeting]] on May 29, 2017,<ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no-byline-->|url=http://www.asahi.com/articles/ASK5Y4V8XK5YUCVL019.html|script-title=ja:\u5c06\u68cb\u9023\u76df, \u4f50\u85e4\u4f1a\u9577\u3092\u518d\u4efb \u68ee\u5185\u4e5d\u6bb5\u304c\u5c02\u52d9\u7406\u4e8b\u306b|title=Sh\u014dgi Renmei, Sat\u014d Kaich\u014d wo Sainin Moriuchi Kudan ga Senmuriji ni|language=ja|trans-title=Sato re-elected president of JSA, Moriuchi Kudan chosen to be senior director.|date=May 29, 2017|newspaper=Asahi Shimbun|access-date=October 20, 2017}}</ref> and re-elected once again for another two-year term in June 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/news/2019/06/70_7.html|script-title=ja:\u65e5\u672c\u5c06\u68cb\u9023\u76df\u65b0\u5f79\u54e1\u306e\u304a\u77e5\u3089\u305b|title=Nihon Sh\u014dgi Renmei Shinyakuin no Oshirase|language=ja|trans-title=Announcement of New Japan Shogi Association Board Members|date=June 7, 2019|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion history==\nThe promotion history of Sat\u014d is as follows:<ref name=\"Promotion history\">{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/player/pro/182.html#jsTabE04_02|script-title=ja:\u68cb\u58eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9: \u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149 \u6607\u6bb5\u5c65\u6b74|title=Kishi D\u0113tab\u0113su: Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Sh\u014ddan Rireki|language=ja|trans-title=Professional Shogi Player Database: Yasumitsu Sat\u014d Promotion History|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n* 1982, December: 6-[[Dan (rank)#Modern usage in shogi|ky\u016b]]\n* 1984, July: 1-dan\n* 1987, May 25: 4-dan\n* 1989, April 1: 5-dan\n* 1992, May 25: 6-dan\n* 1993, October 1: 7-dan\n* 1996, April 1: 8-dan\n* 1998, June 18: 9-dan\n\n==Titles and other championships==\nSat\u014d has appeared in major title matches a total of 37 times. He has won the [[Kisei (shogi)|Kisei title]] six times and has qualified for the [[Kisei (shogi)#Lifetime Kisei|Lifetime Kisei title]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shogi.or.jp/faq/index.html#kisen|script-title=ja:\u6c38\u4e16\u79f0\u53f7\u306e\u898f\u5b9a\u306f\u3069\u3046\u306a\u3063\u3066\u3044\u308b\u306e\u3067\u3057\u3087\u3046\u304b\u3002|title=Eisei Sh\u014dg\u014d no Kitei wa D\u014d Natteriru Desh\u014dka.|trans-title=What are the requirements for lifetime titles?|language=ja|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109172825/http://www.shogi.or.jp/faq/index.html|archive-date=January 9, 2016|access-date=October 4, 2017}}</ref> He has also won the [[Meijin (shogi)|Meijin]], [[Kioh]] and [[Osho (shogi)|Osho]] titles twice each and the [[Ry\u016b\u014d]] title once.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/player/pro/182.html#anc01|script-title=ja:\u68cb\u58eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9: \u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149 \u30bf\u30a4\u30c8\u30eb\u5c65\u6b74|title=Kishi D\u0113tab\u0113su: Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Taitoru Rireki|language=ja|trans-title=Professional Shogi Player Database: Yasumitsu Sat\u014d Major Title History|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=October 19, 2017}}</ref> In addition to major titles, Sat\u014d has won twelve other shogi championships during his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/player/pro/182.html#anc02|script-title=ja:\u68cb\u58eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9: \u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149 \u512a\u52dd\u5c65\u6b74|title=Kishi D\u0113tab\u0113su: Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Y\u016bsh\u014d Rireki|language=ja|trans-title=Professional Shogi Player Database: Yasumitsu Sat\u014d Championship History|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=October 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Major titles===\n{|  class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title || Years || Number of times overall\n|-\n| [[Ry\u016b\u014d]]\n| 1993\n| 1\n|-\n| [[Meijin (shogi)|Meijin]]\n| 1998\u201399\n| 2\n|-\n| [[Kisei (shogi)|Kisei]]\n| 2002-07\n| 6\n|-\n| [[Kioh]]\n| 2006\u201307\n| 2\n|-\n| [[Osho (shogi)|Osho]]\n| 2001, 2011\n| 2\n|}\n\n===Other championships===\n{|  class=\"wikitable\"\n!Tournament || Years ||Number of times\n|-\n|<sup>*</sup>{{ill|Daiwa Securities Strongest Player Cup|ja|\u5927\u548c\u8a3c\u5238\u676f\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u5c06\u68cb\u30fb\u6700\u5f37\u6226}}\n|2012\n|1\n|-\n|{{ill|Ginga-sen|ja|\u9280\u6cb3\u6226}}\n| 2003, 2008, 2010\n|3\n|-\n| [[NHK Cup (shogi)|NHK Cup]]\n| 2006\u201307, 2016\n|3\n|-\n|<sup>*</sup>{{ill|Hayazashi Shineisen|ja|\u65e9\u6307\u3057\u5c06\u68cb\u9078\u624b\u6a29#\u65e9\u6307\u3057\u65b0\u92ed\u6226}}\n|1990-91\n|2\n|-\n| {{ill|JT Nihon Series|ja|JT\u5c06\u68cb\u65e5\u672c\u30b7\u30ea\u30fc\u30ba}}\n| 2004, 2006\n|2\n|-\n|<sup>*</sup>{{ill|All Star Kachinuki-sen|ja|\u30aa\u30fc\u30eb\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u52dd\u3061\u629c\u304d\u6226}}\n|1999\n|1\n|}\nNote: Tournaments marked with an asterisk (*) are no longer held.\n\n==Awards and honors==\nSat\u014d has received numerous awards and honors throughout his career for his accomplishments in both on an off the shogi board. These include the [[Annual Shogi Awards]] given out by the JSA for performance in official games and other awards given out by governmental organizations, etc. for contributions made to Japanese society.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/player/pro/182.html#anc03|script-title=ja:\u68cb\u58eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9: \u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149 \u5c06\u68cb\u5927\u8cde|title=Kishi D\u0113tab\u0113su: Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Sh\u014dgi Taish\u014d|language=ja|trans-title=Professional Shogi Player Database: Yasumitsu Sat\u014d Annual Shogi Awards|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=October 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/player/pro/182.html#anc04|script-title=ja:\u68cb\u58eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9: \u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149 \u305d\u306e\u4ed6\u8868\u5f70|title=Kishi D\u0113tab\u0113su: Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Sonota Hy\u014dsh\u014d|language=ja|trans-title=Professional Shogi Player Database: Yasumitsu Sat\u014d Other Awards|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=October 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Annual Shogi Awards===\n*18th Annual Awards (April 1990 \u2014 March 1991): Best New Player\n*20th Annual Awards (April 1992 \u2014 March 1993): Technique Award\n*21st Annual Awards (April 1993 \u2014 March 1994): Most Games Won, Most Games Played, Most Consecutive Games Won, Distinguished Service Award  \n*23rd Annual Awards (April 1995 \u2014 March 1996): Technique Award\n*25th Annual Awards (April 1997 \u2014 March 1998): Technique Award\n*26th Annual Awards (April 1998 \u2014 March 1999): Distinguished Service Award \n*29th Annual Awards (April 2001 \u2014 March 2002): Most Consecutive Games Won, Technique Award\n*30th Annual Awards (April 2002 \u2014 March 2003): Fighting-spirit Award\n*32nd Annual Awards (April 2004 \u2014 March 2005): Technique Award\n*33rd Annual Awards (April 2005 \u2014 March 2006): Fighting-spirit Award\n*34th Annual Awards (April 2006 \u2014 March 2007): Player of the Year, Most Games Played, Most Games Won, [[Annual Shogi Awards#K\u014dz\u014d Masuda Awards|K\u014dz\u014d Masuda Award]]\n*35th Annual Awards (April 2007 \u2014 March 2008): Player of the Year\n*37th Annual Awards (April 2009 \u2014 March 2010): Game of the Year\n*39th Annual Awards (April 2011 \u2014 March 2012): K\u014dz\u014d Masuda Award<ref>{{cite news|last=Morita|first=Keishi|url=http://www.sankei.com/life/news/170720/lif1707200013-n1.html|script-title=ja:\u65e5\u672c\u5c06\u68cb\u9023\u76df\u4f1a\u9577\uff65\u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149 \u72ec\u5275\u7684\u306a\u6307\u3057\u624b\u3067\u540d\u8a89\u306e\u8cde|title=Nihon Sh\u014dgi Renmei Kaich\u014d\uff65Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Dokusoteki na Sashite de Meiyo no Sh\u014d|language=ja|trans-title=JSA president Yasumitsu Sat\u014d wins prestigious award for original moves|date=July 20, 2017|newspaper=[[Sankei Shimbun]]|access-date=October 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Other awards===\n*1998: [[Yawata, Kyoto|Yawata City]] Meritorius Citizen Award\n*2003: Shogi Honor Fighting-spirit Award (Awarded by JSA in recognition of winning 600 official games as a professional)\n*2007: [[Kyoto Prefecture]] Culture Award\n*2009: Shogi Honor Fighting-spirit Award (Awarded by JSA in recognition of winning 800 official games as a professional)\n*2011: 25 Years Service Award (Awarded by the JSA in recognition of being an active professional for twenty-five years)\n*2017: Japanese government's [[Medals of Honor (Japan)#Purple ribbon|Medal of Honor with Purple Ribbons]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Yamamura|first=Hideki|url=https://mainichi.jp/articles/20170428/k00/00m/040/173000c|script-title=ja:\u7d2b\u7dac\u8912\u7ae0 \u5c06\u68cb\u68cb\u58eb\uff65\u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149\u3055\u3093 \uff62\u5922\u4e0e\u3048\u308b\u5b58\u5728\u306b\uff63|title=Shijuh\u014dsh\u014d Sh\u014dgi Kishi\uff65Sat\u014d Yasumitsu san \"Yume Ataeru Sonzai ni\"|language=ja|trans-title=Shogi professional Yasumitsu Sato awarded Medal of Honor with Purple Ribbons|date=April 28, 2017|newspaper=Mainichi Shimbun|access-date=October 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Year-end prize money and game fee ranking==\nSat\u014d has finished in the \"Top 10\" of the JSA's {{ill|year-end prize money and game fee rankings|ja|\u5c06\u68cb\u754c#\u7372\u5f97\u8cde\u91d1\u3068\u5bfe\u5c40\u6599}} each year from 1993 to 2014, and then again in 2017. He also has finished in the \"Top 3\" eight times.