Sh\u014dkin - Taikyokury\u014d Besuto 10|script-title=ja:2011\u5e74\u7372\u5f97\u8cde\u91d1\u30fb\u5bfe\u5c40\u6599\u30d9\u30b9\u30c810|trans-title= 2012 Prize Money/Game Fees Top 10|language=ja|date=February 18, 2013|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 3, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2013 || \u00a527,200,000 || 6th<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shogi.or.jp/topics/news/2014/02/201310.html|title=2013nen Kakutoku Sh\u014dkin - Taikyokury\u014d Besuto 10|script-title=ja:2013\u5e74\u7372\u5f97\u8cde\u91d1\u30fb\u5bfe\u5c40\u6599\u30d9\u30b9\u30c810|trans-title= 2013 Prize Money/Game Fees Top 10|language=ja|date=February 7, 2014|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 3, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2014 || \u00a516,430,000 || 9th<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shogi.or.jp/topics/news/2015/02/201410.html|title=2014nen Kakutoku Sh\u014dkin - Taikyokury\u014d Besuto 10|script-title=ja:2014\u5e74\u7372\u5f97\u8cde\u91d1\u30fb\u5bfe\u5c40\u6599\u30d9\u30b9\u30c810|trans-title= 2014 Prize Money/Game Fees Top 10|language=ja|date=February 3, 2015|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 3, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017 || \u00a519, 670,000 || 10th<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/news/2018/02/201710.html|title=2017nen Kakutoku Sh\u014dkin - Taikyokury\u014d Besuto 10|script-title=ja:2017\u5e74\u7372\u5f97\u8cde\u91d1\u30fb\u5bfe\u5c40\u6599\u30d9\u30b9\u30c810|trans-title= 2017 Prize Money/Game Fees Top 10|language=ja|date=February 6, 2018|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=February 7, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n*Note: All amounts are given in [[Japanese yen]] and include prize money and fees earned from official tournaments and games held from January 1 to December 31.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*ShogiHub: [http://shogihub.com/players/5 Professional Player Info \u00b7 Sato, Yasumitsu]\n*[http://shinshikishi.cafe.coocan.jp/ Yasumitsu Sat\u014d Supporters' Page] {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{Professional Shogi Players|state=collapsed}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sato, Yasumitsu}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Japanese shogi players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Professional shogi players]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Medal with Purple Ribbon]]\n[[Category:Professional shogi players from Kyoto Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Meijin (shogi)]]\n[[Category:Ry\u016b\u014d]]\n[[Category:Kisei (shogi)]]\n[[Category:Ki\u014d]]\n[[Category:\u014csh\u014d]]\n[[Category:Lifetime titles]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the K\u014dz\u014d Masuda Award]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox shogi professional\n| name             = Yasumitsu Sat\u014d\n| image            =File:SHOGI Proffesional Yasumitsu Satoh.jpg\n| caption          = Sat\u014d at an October 2015 event.\n| born             = {{birth date and age | 1969 | 10 | 01 | mf=yes}} \n| hometown         = [[Yawata, Kyoto]]\n| nationality      = [[Japanese people|Japanese]]\n| pro_date         = {{event date and age | 1987 | 3 | 25 | 1969 | 10 | 01}}\n| badge_no         = 182\n| teacher          = {{ill | Kaish\u016b Tanaka|ja| \u7530\u4e2d\u9b41\u79c0}} \n| lifetime_titles  = [[Kisei (shogi)#Lifetime Kisei|Lifetime Kisei]]\n| rank             = 9 [[dan (rank)#Modern usage in shogi|dan]]\n| no_titles        = 13\n| tournaments      = 12\n| meijinclass      = A\n| ryuoclass        = 1\n| jsa              = 182\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Yasumitsu Sat\u014d'''|\u4f50\u85e4 \u5eb7\u5149|Sat\u014d Yasumitsu | born October 1, 1969}} is a Japanese [[professional shogi player]] from [[Yawata, Kyoto|Yawata City]] in [[Kyoto Prefecture]], [[Japan]]. He is currently the president of the [[Japan Shogi Association]]. He became a professional in 1987 and is ranked 9-[[Dan (rank)#Modern usage in shogi|dan]]. He has won 13 major titles, is a former [[Meijin]] title holder, and has qualified for the [[Kisei (shogi)#Lifetime Kisei|Lifetime Kisei]] title.\n\n==Early life==\nSat\u014d was born in [[Yawata, Kyoto|Yawata City]] in [[Kyoto Prefecture]] on October 1, 1969.<ref name=\"JSA Database\">{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/player/pro/182.html|script-title=ja:\u68cb\u58eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9: \u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149|title=Kishi D\u0113tab\u0113su: Sat\u014d Yasumitsu|language=ja|trans-title=Professional Shogi Player Database: Yasumitsu Sat\u014d|publisher=[[Japan Shogi Association]]|access-date=October 4, 2017}}</ref> He finished third in the 6th {{ill|Elementary Student Meijin Tournament|ja|\u5c0f\u5b66\u751f\u5c06\u68cb\u540d\u4eba\u6226}} in 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://joshi-shogi.com/event/10th_aomori.html#more|script-title=ja:\u7b2c10\u56de\u8a18\u5ff5\u9752\u68ee\u770c\u5c06\u68cb\u307e\u3064\u308a|title=Dai Jikkai Kinen Aomori-ken Sh\u014dgi Matsuri|language=ja|trans-title=10th Aomori Prefecture Shogi Festival|date=September 21, 2008|publisher=Ladies Shogi Professional-players Association|quote=\u5199\u771f\u30ad\u30e3\u30d7\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3: 1981\u5e74\u306e\u5c0f\u5b66\u751f\u540d\u4eba\u6226, \u4f50\u85e4\u68cb\u738b\u306f3\u4f4d, \u6e96\u512a\u52dd\u306f\u4e2d\u4e95\u73fe\u5973\u6d41\u516d\u6bb5\u3068\u3044\u3046\u8a71\u984c\u306b [Photo caption: The converstation turned to the 1981 Elementary Student Meijin Tournament where Sat\u014d Ki\u014d finished third and Nakai Female Professional 6d finished second]|access-date=November 8, 2017}}</ref> His experience in the tournament led him to want become a shogi professional, and he entered the [[Japan Shogi Association#Headquarters and other offices|Kansai branch]] of the Japan Shogi Association's [[Professional shogi player#Apprenticeship|apprentice school]] at the rank of 6-[[Dan (rank)#Modern usage in shogi|ky\u016b]] in December 1982 as a [[protegee]] of shogi professional {{ill|Kaish\u016b Tanaka|ja|\u7530\u4e2d\u9b41\u79c0}} in December 1982.<ref name=\"2016databook\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NoIRCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA56|script-title=ja:\u73fe\u5f79\u30d7\u30ed\u68cb\u58eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d6\u30c3\u30af2016 [\u4e0a] \u3042-\u305f|title=Geneki Pur\u014d Kishi D\u0113taBukku 2016 [J\u014d] A-Ta Gy\u014d|language=ja|trans-title=2016 Active Shogi Professional Databook [First volume] Letter \"A\" to Letter \"Ta\"|page=56|year=2015|publisher=MyNabi Publishing/Japan Shogi Association|via=[[Google Books]]|access-date=November 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Shogi professional==\nSat\u014d's first appearance a major title match was in 1990 as the challenger to [[K\u014dji Tanigawa]] for the [[\u014ci (shogi)|31st \u014ci title]], but he lost the match 4 games to 3.<ref name=\"2016databook\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/oui/#aswift_0_anchor|script-title=ja:\u738b\u4f4d\u6226: \u904e\u53bb\u306e\u7d50\u679c|title=\u014cisen: Kako no Kekka|language=ja|trans-title=\u014ci tournament: Past results|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref> That same year, he won his first tournament as a professional when he defeated [[Toshiyuki Moriuchi]] to win the {{ill|9th Hayazashi Shinei Tournament|ja|\u65e9\u6307\u3057\u5c06\u68cb\u9078\u624b\u6a29#\u65e9\u6307\u3057\u65b0\u92ed\u6226}}, a [[Rapid chess|quick-play type]] tournament for young players under the age of thirty. He repeated as champion the following year when he won the 10th Hayazashi Shinei Tournament when he defeated [[Taku Morishita]] in the final.<ref name=\"2016databook\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/finished/12/|script-title=ja:\u65e9\u6307\u3057\u5c06\u68cb\u9078\u624b\u6a29\u6226\uff65\u65e9\u6307\u3057\u65b0\u92ed\u6226|title=Hayazahi Sh\u014dgi Senshukensen\uff65Hayazashi Shineisen|language=ja|trans-title=Quick-play Shogi Tournament\uff65Quick-play Young Professional Tournament|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/finished/12/rekidai.html|script-title=ja:\u65e9\u6307\u3057\u5c06\u68cb\u9078\u624b\u6a29\u6226\uff65\u65e9\u6307\u3057\u65b0\u92ed\u6226: \u6b74\u4ee3\u512a\u52dd\u8005\u4e00\u89a7|title=Hayazahi Sh\u014dgi Senshukensen\uff65Hayazashi Shineisen: Rekidai Y\u016bsh\u014dsha Ichiran|language=ja|trans-title=Quick-play Shogi Tournament\uff65Quick-play Young Professional Tournament: Winners list|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Sat\u014d challenged [[Yoshiharu Habu]] for the [[Ry\u016b\u014d|6th Ry\u016b\u014d title]] and won the match 4 games to 2 for his first major title. The same two players met in the title matches for the 7th Ry\u016b\u014d (1994) and 8th Ry\u016b\u014d (1995). Challenger Habu was able to recapture his title by the score of 4 games to 2 in 1994 and then defend it by the same score in 1995.<ref name=\"2016databook\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/ryuuou|script-title=ja:\u7adc\u738b\u6226: \u904e\u53bb\u306e\u7d50\u679c|title=Ry\u016b\u014dsen: Kako no Kekka|language=ja|trans-title=Ry\u016b\u014d tournament: Past results|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Sat\u014d challenged Habu for the [[:\u014ci (shogi)|38th \u014ci title]] Habu, but lost the match by the score of 4 games to 1.<ref name=\"Oi\">{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/oui|script-title=ja:\u738b\u4f4d\u6226: \u904e\u53bb\u306e\u7d50\u679c|title=\u014cisen: Kako no Kekka|language=ja|trans-title=\u014ci tournament: Past results|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 6, 2017}}</ref> The two met once again the following year for the 39th \u014ci title, but Habu defended his title by the score 4 games to 2.<ref name=\"Oi\" /> That same year, Sat\u014d was the challenger to Habu for the [[Ki\u014d|24th Ki\u014d title]], but lost the match 3 games to 0.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/kiou/|script-title=ja:\u68cb\u738b\u6226: \u904e\u53bb\u306e\u7d50\u679c|title=Ki\u014d: Kako no Kekka|language=ja|trans-title=Ki\u014d tournament: Past results|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 6, 2017}}</ref> Sat\u014d once again challenged Habu for the Ki\u014d title in 2001. Sat\u014d won the first game of the 27th Ki\u014d match, but Habu then won the next three games to defend his title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/kiou/27hon/index.html|script-title=ja:\u7b2c27\u671f\u68cb\u738b\u6226 \u6311\u6226\u8005\u6c7a\u5b9a\u30c8\u30fc\u30ca\u30e1\u30f3\u30c8 / \u4e94\u756a\u52dd\u8ca0|title=Dai Nij\u016bnanaki Ki\u014dsen Ch\u014dsensha Kettei T\u014dnamento/Goban Sh\u014dbu|language=ja|trans-title=27th Ki\u014d Tournament: Challenger Tournament/5-game Match|year=2001|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn just his second year in [[Meijin (shogi)#Qualifying|Meijin Class A]], Sat\u014d earned the right to challenge Tanigawa for the [[Meijin (shogi)|56th Meijin title]] (1998) by defeating Habu in a one-game playoff after both players finished league play with a record of 6 wins and 3 losses.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RyaABAAAQBAJ&pg=614|script-title=ja:\u5c06\u68cb\u9806\u4f4d\u622630\u5e74\u53f2 1984-1997\u5e74\u7de8|title=Sh\u014dgi Jun'isen Sanj\u016bnenshi 1984-1997nenhen|language=ja|trans-title=30 Year History of Meijin League Play: Years 1984-1997|year=2014|page=614|publisher=MyNabi Publishing/Japan Shogi Association|isbn=978-4-8399-5306-5|via=[[Google Books]]|access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref> Sat\u014d then proceeded to defeat Tanigawa 4 games to 3 to win the Meijin title for the first time. The following year, Sat\u014d and Tanigawa met again for the 57th Meijin title (1999), with Sat\u014d defending his title by the score of 4 games to 3. Sat\u014d, however, was unable to successfully defend his title for the third consecutive year when he lost to [[Tadahisa Maruyama]] 4 games to 3 in the 58th Meijin title match (200).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/junni/#jo_tab|script-title=ja:\u540d\u4eba\u6226\uff65\u9806\u4f4d\u6226: \u904e\u53bb\u306e\u7d50\u679c|title=Meijinsen\uff65Jun'isen: Kako no Kekka|language=ja|trans-title=Meijin Match\uff65Meijin League Play: Past results|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSat\u014d was the challenger in the 47th \u014csh\u014d (1997) and 49th \u014csh\u014d (1999) title matches against Habu, but lost by the scores of 4 games to 1 and 4 games to 0, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/oushou|script-title=ja:\u738b\u5c06\u6226: \u904e\u53bb\u306e\u7d50\u679c|title=\u014csh\u014dsen: Kako no Kekka|language=ja|trans-title=\u014csh\u014d Tournament: Past results|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref> In 2002, Sat\u014d finished the 51st \u014csh\u014d challenger league play undefeated with six wins to once again challenge to Habu for the title. Sato won the first two games of the match and then split the next four to win the match 4 games to 2,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/oushou/51/hon.html|script-title=ja:\u7b2c51\u671f\u738b\u5c06\u6226 \u4e03\u756a\u52dd\u8ca0\uff65\u6311\u6226\u8005\u6c7a\u5b9a\u30ea\u30fc\u30b0\u6226|title=Dai Goj\u016bikki \u014csh\u014dsen\uff65Nanaban Sh\u014dbu\uff65Ch\u014dsensha Kettei R\u012bgusen|language=ja|trans-title=51st \u014csh\u014d 7-game Match\uff65Challenger League Play|year=2001|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line-->|url=http://www.shikoku-np.co.jp/national/life_topic/20020312000443|script-title=ja:\u4f50\u85e4\u304c\u7fbd\u751f\u304b\u3089\u738b\u5c06\u4f4d\u596a\u53d6 / \u5c06\u68cb\u306e\u738b\u5c06\u6226\u7b2c6\u5c40|title=Sat\u014d ga Habu kara  \u014csh\u014di Dasshu / Sh\u014dgi no \u014csh\u014dsen Dai Rokkyoku|language=ja|trans-title=Sat\u014d takes \u014csh\u014d title from Habu / Shogi \u014csh\u014d match Game 6|date=March 12, 2002|newspaper=[[List of newspapers in Japan#Prefecture papers of Shikoku|Shikoku Shimbun]]|access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref> thus ending his title match losing streak to Habu at eight.<ref name=\"2016databook\" /> The following year, however, Habu was successful in retaking the title from Sat\u014d, winning the 52nd \u014csh\u014d match 4 games to 0.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/match/oushou/52/hon.html|script-title=ja:\u7b2c52\u671f\u738b\u5c06\u6226 \u4e03\u756a\u52dd\u8ca0\uff65\u6311\u6226\u8005\u6c7a\u5b9a\u30ea\u30fc\u30b0\u6226|title=Dai Goj\u016bniki \u014csh\u014dsen\uff65Nanaban Sh\u014dbu\uff65Ch\u014dsensha Kettei R\u012bgusen|language=ja|trans-title=52nd \u014csh\u014d 7-game Match\uff65Challenger League Play|year=2002|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref> Sat\u014d and Habu met again in 55th \u014csh\u014d (2006) and 56th \u014csh\u014d (2007) title matches with Habu defending his title each time by the score of 4 games to 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.igoshogi.net/topics/detail.php?ID=421|script-title=ja:\u7b2c55\u671f\u738b\u5c06\u6226...\u7fbd\u751f\u738b\u5c06, \u9632\u885b|title=Dai Goj\u016bgoki \u014csh\u014d ... Habu \u014csh\u014d, B\u014dei|language=ja|trans-title=55th \u014csh\u014d Match ... Habu \u014cish\u014d defends title|date=March 23, 2006|publisher=Igo & Shogi Channel|access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.igoshogi.net/topics/detail.php?ID=524|script-title=ja:\u7b2c56\u671f\u738b\u5c06\u6226...\u7fbd\u751f\u738b\u5c06\u306e\u9632\u885b|title=Dai Goj\u016bgoki \u014csh\u014d ... Habu \u014csh\u014d no B\u014dei|language=ja|trans-title=56th \u014csh\u014d Match ... Habu \u014cish\u014d defends title|date=March 22, 2007|publisher=Igo & Shogi Channel|access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Sat\u014d defeated [[Toshiyuki Moriuchi]] (the reigning [[Meijin (shogi)|Meijin]] at the time) to win the [[NHK Cup (shogi)|56th NHK Cup Shogi TV tournament]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.igoshogi.net/topics/detail.php?ID=522&is=1|script-title=ja:\u7b2c56\u56deNHK\u676f\u5c06\u68cb\uff34...\u85e4\u68cb\u8056\u306e\u512a\u52dd|title=Dai Goj\u016brokkai NHKhai Sh\u014dgi T ... Sat\u014d Kisei no Y\u016bsh\u014d|language=ja|trans-title=Sato Kisei Wins 56th NHK Cup|date=March 19, 2007|publisher=Igo & Shogi Channel|access-date=November 7, 2017}}</ref> He defeated [[Daisuke Suzuki (shogi)|Daisuke Suzuki]] the following year to defend his title and become just the third player ever to win the tournament in consecutive years, with the championship game between the two being the first NHK shogi tournament game ever to be [[Live television|broadcast live on TV]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AYbrCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA372|script-title=ja:\u5c06\u68cb\u30bf\u30a4\u30c8\u30eb\u622630\u5e74\u53f2 1998\uff5e2013\u5e74\u7de8|title=Sh\u014dgi Taitorusen Sanj\u016bnenshi 1998-2013nenhen|language=ja|trans-title=30 Year History of Shogi Major Title Matches: Years 1998-2013|year=2014|publisher=MyNabi Publishing/Japan Shogi Association|page=372|isbn=978-4-8399-5097-2|via=Google Books|access-date=November 7, 2017}}</ref> Sat\u014d won the tournament for a third time in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line-->|url=http://www.asahi.com/articles/DA3S12868596.html|script-title=ja:\u4f50\u85e4\u4e5d\u6bb5\u304c\u512a\u52dd \u5c06\u68cb\uff65NHK\u676f|title=Sat\u014d Kudan ga Y\u016bsh\u014d, Shogi\uff65NHKhai|language=ja|trans-title=Sato 9d Wins Shogi NHK Cup|date=March 30, 2017|newspaper=[[Asahi Shimbun]]|access-date=November 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSat\u014d became the ninth professional player to record 1000 victories in official games when he defeated [[Akihito Hirose]] in a Meijin Class A game on July 28, 2017. Sat\u014d is the first player to accomplish such a feat since Habu did so in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/news/2017/07/1000_3.html|script-title=ja:\u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149\u4e5d\u6bb5, 1000\u52dd\uff08\u7279\u5225\u5c06\u68cb\u6804\u8a89\u8cde\uff09\u3092\u9054\u6210\uff01|title=Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Kudan, Sensh\u014d (Tokubetsu Sh\u014dgi Eiyosh\u014d) wo Tassei!|language=ja|trans-title=Yasumitsu Sat\u014d Wins 1000 Official Game (Special Shogi Award)|date=July 29, 2017|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=November 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Yamamura|first=Hideki|url=https://mainichi.jp/articles/20170729/k00/00m/040/157000c|script-title=ja:\u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149\u4e5d\u6bb5\u304c1000\u52dd\u9054\u6210, \u53f2\u4e0a9\u4eba\u76ee|title=Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Kudan ga Sensh\u014d Tassei, Shij\u014d Ky\u016bninme|language=ja|trans-title=Yasumitsu Sato 9d Becomes 9th Player to Reach 1000 Wins|date=July 29, 2017|newspaper=[[Mainichi Shimbun]]|access-date=November 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Playing style ==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=August 2018}}\nHe was known to use a lot of [[j\u014dseki]] positions as a young player, but since 2005 he has often opted for choosing to play creatively with the standard strategies. His new move [[Cheerful Central Rook#5. P-96|5. P-96]] for [[Cheerful Central Rook]] has been widely adopted by many professional players. From a young age he has been known for the depth of his reading, which is called  his \"minute\" or \"meticulous\" style, and of which is said that he can \"read a billion of three-move series in a second\".\n\n==JSA president==\nSat\u014d served as the chairman of the {{ill|Shogi Professional Players' Association|ja|\u65e5\u672c\u5c06\u68cb\u9023\u76df#\u68cb\u58eb\u4f1a}} from April 2011 until January 2017.<ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line-->|url=https://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXLASFG06H8D_W7A200C1000000/|script-title=ja:\u5c06\u68cb\u9023\u76df, \u65b0\u4f1a\u9577\u306b\u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149\u4e5d\u6bb5 \uff62\u4fe1\u983c\u56de\u5fa9\u306b\u5168\u529b\uff63 |title=Sh\u014dgi Renmai, Shinkaicho ni Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Kudan \"Shinrai Kaifuku ni Zenryoku\"|language=ja|trans-title=Japan Shogi Association selects Yasumitsu Sat\u014d 9d as new president. Promises to \"use all his power to restore JSA reputation\"|date=February 6, 2017|newspaper=[[The Nikkei]]|quote=2011\u5e74\u304b\u3089\u68cb\u58eb\u4f1a\u4f1a\u9577\u3092\u52d9\u3081\u3066\u3044\u305f. [Served as chairman of Shogi Professional Players' Association since 2011]|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/news/2017/02/post_1508.html|script-title=ja:\u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149\u68cb\u58eb\u4f1a\u4f1a\u9577\u306e\u8f9e\u4efb\u306b\u95a2\u3059\u308b\u304a\u77e5\u3089\u305b|title=Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Kishikai Kaicho no Jinin ni Kansuru Oshirase|language=ja|trans-title=Announcement regarding Shogi Professional Players' Association Chairman Yasumitsu Sat\u014d's resignation|date=February 1, 2017|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref> He announced his candidacy for the [[Japan Shogi Association#General meetings and the board of directors|JSA's board of directors]] on January 19, 2017, a day after [[K\u014dji Tanigawa]] announced his resignation as JSA president to accept responsibility for the [[Ry\u016b\u014d#29th Ry\u016b\u014d challenger controversy|29th Ry\u016b\u014d challenger controversy]].<ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line-->|url=http://www.asahi.com/articles/DA3S12755945.html|script-title=ja:\u5c06\u68cb\u9023\u76df\u7406\u4e8b\u9078, \u4f50\u85e4\u4e5d\u6bb5\u51fa\u99ac\u3078|title=Sh\u014dgi Renmei Rijisen, Sat\u014d Kudan Sh\u016btsuba e|language=ja|trans-title=Sato 9d Announces Candidacy for JSA Board of Directors|date=January 20, 2017|newspaper=Asahi Shimbun|url-access=subscription|access-date=November 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Yamamura|first1=Hideki|last2=Mogami|first2=Satoshi|url=http://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20170118/p2a/00m/0na/013000c|title=Head of shogi association resigns after top player cleared of cheating|date=January 18, 2017|newspaper=Mainichi Shimbun|access-date=November 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSat\u014d was elected to the JSA's Board of Directors at an emergency meeting of the organization's members on February 6, 2017, and was later chosen by the board at a meeting held the same day to serve out the remainder of Tanigawa's term as JSA president.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/news/2017/02/post_1510.html|script-title=ja:\u65e5\u672c\u5c06\u68cb\u9023\u76df\u65b0\u5f79\u54e1\u306e\u304a\u77e5\u3089\u305b|title=Nihon Sh\u014dgi Renmei Shiyakuin no Oshirase|language=ja|trans-title=Announcement of New Japan Shogi Association Board Members|date=February 6, 2017|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=November 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"JT\">{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer; No by-line-->|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2017/02/07/national/elite-player-tapped-new-shogi-body-chief-defamation-scandal/|title=Elite player tapped as new 'shogi' body chief after defamation scandal|date=February 7, 2017|newspaper=[[The Japan Times]]|agency=[[Kyodo News]]|access-date=October 4, 2017}}</ref> He was re-elected as president for a full two-year term at the [[Japan Shogi Association#General meetings and the board of directors|JSA's general meeting]] on May 29, 2017,<ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no-byline-->|url=http://www.asahi.com/articles/ASK5Y4V8XK5YUCVL019.html|script-title=ja:\u5c06\u68cb\u9023\u76df, \u4f50\u85e4\u4f1a\u9577\u3092\u518d\u4efb \u68ee\u5185\u4e5d\u6bb5\u304c\u5c02\u52d9\u7406\u4e8b\u306b|title=Sh\u014dgi Renmei, Sat\u014d Kaich\u014d wo Sainin Moriuchi Kudan ga Senmuriji ni|language=ja|trans-title=Sato re-elected president of JSA, Moriuchi Kudan chosen to be senior director.|date=May 29, 2017|newspaper=Asahi Shimbun|access-date=October 20, 2017}}</ref> and re-elected once again for another two-year term in June 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/news/2019/06/70_7.html|script-title=ja:\u65e5\u672c\u5c06\u68cb\u9023\u76df\u65b0\u5f79\u54e1\u306e\u304a\u77e5\u3089\u305b|title=Nihon Sh\u014dgi Renmei Shinyakuin no Oshirase|language=ja|trans-title=Announcement of New Japan Shogi Association Board Members|date=June 7, 2019|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion history==\nThe promotion history of Sat\u014d is as follows:<ref name=\"Promotion history\">{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/player/pro/182.html#jsTabE04_02|script-title=ja:\u68cb\u58eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9: \u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149 \u6607\u6bb5\u5c65\u6b74|title=Kishi D\u0113tab\u0113su: Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Sh\u014ddan Rireki|language=ja|trans-title=Professional Shogi Player Database: Yasumitsu Sat\u014d Promotion History|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n* 1982, December: 6-[[Dan (rank)#Modern usage in shogi|ky\u016b]]\n* 1984, July: 1-dan\n* 1987, May 25: 4-dan\n* 1989, April 1: 5-dan\n* 1992, May 25: 6-dan\n* 1993, October 1: 7-dan\n* 1996, April 1: 8-dan\n* 1998, June 18: 9-dan\n\n==Titles and other championships==\nSat\u014d has appeared in major title matches a total of 37 times. He has won the [[Kisei (shogi)|Kisei title]] six times and has qualified for the [[Kisei (shogi)#Lifetime Kisei|Lifetime Kisei title]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shogi.or.jp/faq/index.html#kisen|script-title=ja:\u6c38\u4e16\u79f0\u53f7\u306e\u898f\u5b9a\u306f\u3069\u3046\u306a\u3063\u3066\u3044\u308b\u306e\u3067\u3057\u3087\u3046\u304b\u3002|title=Eisei Sh\u014dg\u014d no Kitei wa D\u014d Natteriru Desh\u014dka.|trans-title=What are the requirements for lifetime titles?|language=ja|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109172825/http://www.shogi.or.jp/faq/index.html|archive-date=January 9, 2016|access-date=October 4, 2017}}</ref> He has also won the [[Meijin (shogi)|Meijin]], [[Kioh]] and [[Osho (shogi)|Osho]] titles twice each and the [[Ry\u016b\u014d]] title once.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/player/pro/182.html#anc01|script-title=ja:\u68cb\u58eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9: \u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149 \u30bf\u30a4\u30c8\u30eb\u5c65\u6b74|title=Kishi D\u0113tab\u0113su: Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Taitoru Rireki|language=ja|trans-title=Professional Shogi Player Database: Yasumitsu Sat\u014d Major Title History|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=October 19, 2017}}</ref> In addition to major titles, Sat\u014d has won twelve other shogi championships during his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/player/pro/182.html#anc02|script-title=ja:\u68cb\u58eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9: \u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149 \u512a\u52dd\u5c65\u6b74|title=Kishi D\u0113tab\u0113su: Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Y\u016bsh\u014d Rireki|language=ja|trans-title=Professional Shogi Player Database: Yasumitsu Sat\u014d Championship History|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=October 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Major titles===\n{|  class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title || Years || Number of times overall\n|-\n| [[Ry\u016b\u014d]]\n| 1993\n| 1\n|-\n| [[Meijin (shogi)|Meijin]]\n| 1998\u201399\n| 2\n|-\n| [[Kisei (shogi)|Kisei]]\n| 2002-07\n| 6\n|-\n| [[Kioh]]\n| 2006\u201307\n| 2\n|-\n| [[Osho (shogi)|Osho]]\n| 2001, 2011\n| 2\n|}\n\n===Other championships===\n{|  class=\"wikitable\"\n!Tournament || Years ||Number of times\n|-\n|<sup>*</sup>{{ill|Daiwa Securities Strongest Player Cup|ja|\u5927\u548c\u8a3c\u5238\u676f\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u5c06\u68cb\u30fb\u6700\u5f37\u6226}}\n|2012\n|1\n|-\n|{{ill|Ginga-sen|ja|\u9280\u6cb3\u6226}}\n| 2003, 2008, 2010\n|3\n|-\n| [[NHK Cup (shogi)|NHK Cup]]\n| 2006\u201307, 2016\n|3\n|-\n|<sup>*</sup>{{ill|Hayazashi Shineisen|ja|\u65e9\u6307\u3057\u5c06\u68cb\u9078\u624b\u6a29#\u65e9\u6307\u3057\u65b0\u92ed\u6226}}\n|1990-91\n|2\n|-\n| {{ill|JT Nihon Series|ja|JT\u5c06\u68cb\u65e5\u672c\u30b7\u30ea\u30fc\u30ba}}\n| 2004, 2006\n|2\n|-\n|<sup>*</sup>{{ill|All Star Kachinuki-sen|ja|\u30aa\u30fc\u30eb\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u52dd\u3061\u629c\u304d\u6226}}\n|1999\n|1\n|}\nNote: Tournaments marked with an asterisk (*) are no longer held.\n\n==Awards and honors==\nSat\u014d has received numerous awards and honors throughout his career for his accomplishments in both on an off the shogi board. These include the [[Annual Shogi Awards]] given out by the JSA for performance in official games and other awards given out by governmental organizations, etc. for contributions made to Japanese society.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/player/pro/182.html#anc03|script-title=ja:\u68cb\u58eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9: \u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149 \u5c06\u68cb\u5927\u8cde|title=Kishi D\u0113tab\u0113su: Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Sh\u014dgi Taish\u014d|language=ja|trans-title=Professional Shogi Player Database: Yasumitsu Sat\u014d Annual Shogi Awards|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=October 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/player/pro/182.html#anc04|script-title=ja:\u68cb\u58eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9: \u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149 \u305d\u306e\u4ed6\u8868\u5f70|title=Kishi D\u0113tab\u0113su: Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Sonota Hy\u014dsh\u014d|language=ja|trans-title=Professional Shogi Player Database: Yasumitsu Sat\u014d Other Awards|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=October 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Annual Shogi Awards===\n*18th Annual Awards (April 1990 \u2014 March 1991): Best New Player\n*20th Annual Awards (April 1992 \u2014 March 1993): Technique Award\n*21st Annual Awards (April 1993 \u2014 March 1994): Most Games Won, Most Games Played, Most Consecutive Games Won, Distinguished Service Award  \n*23rd Annual Awards (April 1995 \u2014 March 1996): Technique Award\n*25th Annual Awards (April 1997 \u2014 March 1998): Technique Award\n*26th Annual Awards (April 1998 \u2014 March 1999): Distinguished Service Award \n*29th Annual Awards (April 2001 \u2014 March 2002): Most Consecutive Games Won, Technique Award\n*30th Annual Awards (April 2002 \u2014 March 2003): Fighting-spirit Award\n*32nd Annual Awards (April 2004 \u2014 March 2005): Technique Award\n*33rd Annual Awards (April 2005 \u2014 March 2006): Fighting-spirit Award\n*34th Annual Awards (April 2006 \u2014 March 2007): Player of the Year, Most Games Played, Most Games Won, [[Annual Shogi Awards#K\u014dz\u014d Masuda Awards|K\u014dz\u014d Masuda Award]]\n*35th Annual Awards (April 2007 \u2014 March 2008): Player of the Year\n*37th Annual Awards (April 2009 \u2014 March 2010): Game of the Year\n*39th Annual Awards (April 2011 \u2014 March 2012): K\u014dz\u014d Masuda Award<ref>{{cite news|last=Morita|first=Keishi|url=http://www.sankei.com/life/news/170720/lif1707200013-n1.html|script-title=ja:\u65e5\u672c\u5c06\u68cb\u9023\u76df\u4f1a\u9577\uff65\u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149 \u72ec\u5275\u7684\u306a\u6307\u3057\u624b\u3067\u540d\u8a89\u306e\u8cde|title=Nihon Sh\u014dgi Renmei Kaich\u014d\uff65Sat\u014d Yasumitsu Dokusoteki na Sashite de Meiyo no Sh\u014d|language=ja|trans-title=JSA president Yasumitsu Sat\u014d wins prestigious award for original moves|date=July 20, 2017|newspaper=[[Sankei Shimbun]]|access-date=October 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Other awards===\n*1998: [[Yawata, Kyoto|Yawata City]] Meritorius Citizen Award\n*2003: Shogi Honor Fighting-spirit Award (Awarded by JSA in recognition of winning 600 official games as a professional)\n*2007: [[Kyoto Prefecture]] Culture Award\n*2009: Shogi Honor Fighting-spirit Award (Awarded by JSA in recognition of winning 800 official games as a professional)\n*2011: 25 Years Service Award (Awarded by the JSA in recognition of being an active professional for twenty-five years)\n*2017: Japanese government's [[Medals of Honor (Japan)#Purple ribbon|Medal of Honor with Purple Ribbons]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Yamamura|first=Hideki|url=https://mainichi.jp/articles/20170428/k00/00m/040/173000c|script-title=ja:\u7d2b\u7dac\u8912\u7ae0 \u5c06\u68cb\u68cb\u58eb\uff65\u4f50\u85e4\u5eb7\u5149\u3055\u3093 \uff62\u5922\u4e0e\u3048\u308b\u5b58\u5728\u306b\uff63|title=Shijuh\u014dsh\u014d Sh\u014dgi Kishi\uff65Sat\u014d Yasumitsu san \"Yume Ataeru Sonzai ni\"|language=ja|trans-title=Shogi professional Yasumitsu Sato awarded Medal of Honor with Purple Ribbons|date=April 28, 2017|newspaper=Mainichi Shimbun|access-date=October 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Year-end prize money and game fee ranking==\nSat\u014d has finished in the \"Top 10\" of the JSA's {{ill|year-end prize money and game fee rankings|ja|\u5c06\u68cb\u754c#\u7372\u5f97\u8cde\u91d1\u3068\u5bfe\u5c40\u6599}} each year from 1993 to 2014, and then again in 2017. He also has finished in the \"Top 3\" eight times.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Amount !! Rank\n|-\n| 1993 || \u00a521,910,000 || 6th<ref name=\"kishimania\">{{cite web|url=http://kishi-mania.jp/prizemoney|title=Nenkan Kakutoku Sh\u014dkin - Taikyokury\u014d TOP10|script-title=ja:\u5e74\u9593\u7372\u5f97\u8cde\u91d1\u30fb\u5bfe\u5c40\u6599TOP10|trans-title=Annual Prize Money/Game Fees Top 10|language=ja|publisher=Kishi-mania|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/v8JFD|archive-date=May 23, 2014|access-date=December 3, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1994 || \u00a555,130,000 || 2nd<ref name=\"kishimania\" />\n|-\n| 1995 || \u00a533,720,000 || 5th<ref name=\"kishimania\" />\n|-\n| 1996 || \u00a531,040,000 || 5th<ref name=\"kishimania\" />\n|-\n| 1997 || \u00a526,510,000 || 6th<ref name=\"kishimania\" />\n|-\n| 1998 || \u00a557,370,000 || 3rd<ref name=\"kishimania\" />\n|-\n| 1999 || \u00a563,550,000 || 3rd<ref name=\"kishimania\" />\n|-\n| 2000 || \u00a547,440,000 || 4th<ref name=\"kishimania\" />\n|-\n| 2001 || \u00a525,670,000 || 7th<ref name=\"kishimania\" />\n|-\n| 2002 || \u00a555,130,000 || 2nd<ref name=\"kishimania\" />\n|-\n| 2003 || \u00a557,090,000 || 2nd<ref name=\"kishimania\" />\n|-\n| 2004 || \u00a540,510,000 || 4th<ref name=\"kishimania\" />\n|-\n| 2005 || \u00a550,400,000 || 4th<ref name=\"2005-06 Prize Money\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shogi.or.jp/topics/news/2007/03/200620.html|title=2006nen Kakutoku Sh\u014dkin - Taikyokury\u014d Besuto 20|script-title=ja:2006\u5e74\u7372\u5f97\u8cde\u91d1\u